<P></P>
<CENTER><H2>Recommended Books &amp; Articles<BR>on Sustainable Community Development</H2></CENTER>


<P><B><I> Last updated: July 1996</I></B></P>
<P> </P><P></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P> 
<P> </P>
<P>There are many books, reports, and articles available that focus on developing sustainable communities.  The following list identifies resources that we feel are best suited to helping your community plan for and implement economic development strategies that will enhance your local economy, the environment, and quality of life.   In addition, we&#146;ve identified some useful and informative sites on the World Wide Web that offer bibliographies and lists of publications related to sustainable development.</P>

<P>This list of resources is provided as part of the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development&#146;s commitment to ensuring a more sustainable future for communities across the country.  If your community would like to request specific sustainable development assistance, please contact us at the following address:</P>
<UL><P>  Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development
<BR>U.S. Department of Energy
<BR>Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy
<BR>Denver Regional Support Office
<BR>1617 Cole Boulevard
<BR>Golden, CO  80401
<BR>(800) 363-3732
<BR>fax: (303) 275-4830
<BR>Email:  <A HREF="mailto:sustainable.development@hq.doe.gov">
sustainable.development@hq.doe.gov
</A>



<BR>World Wide Web:  <A HREF="
http://www.sustainable.doe.gov">http://www.sustainable.doe.gov</A></P></UL>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P>
<H3><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0"><A
HREF="#Recommended"> Recommended Books</A></H3>
<H3><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0"><A
HREF="#Articles"> Recommended Articles</A></H3>
<H3><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0"><A
HREF="#On-Line"> On-Line Bibliographies</A></H3>
<H3><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0"><A
HREF="#Publications"> On-Line Publications Lists</A></H3><P></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P> 


<H3><A NAME="Recommended"></A> Recommended Books</H3>
<UL>
<LI><P><B></B> <B><I>Bound to the Earth: Creating a Working Partnership of Humanity and Nature</I></B>, 1994, Avon Books.  ISBN 0-38076-971-9.</P>
<P>Using the forest as both metaphor and example, the authors offer a timely and much-needed blueprint and indispensable methods for integrating ourselves into the natural world, mimicking nature&#146;s efficiency in production and recycling, discovering 





new energy sources, developing self-repairing systems and creating goods and services close to home, and limiting the needs of long-distance transportation.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B></B> <B><I>Building Sustainable Communities: An Environmental Guide for Local Governments</I></B>, 1991-1992, Center for the Study of Law and Politics, 2962 Fillmore Street, San Francisco, CA  94123; (415) 775-0791.</P>
<P>Intended for local officials, this set of ten handbooks profiles successful projects and explains how to implement them.  Topics include water conservation, solid waste, transportation, land use, energy, and more.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B></B> <B><I>Choosing a Sustainable Future: The Report of the National Commission on the Environment</I></B>, 1993, Island Press, ISBN 1-55963-232-1.</P>
<P>Presents policy recommendations that can put the United States on a path toward a sustainability and outlines a feasible approach for achieving long-term economic and environmental prosperity.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Cities and Counties: Thinking Globally, Acting Locally</I></B>, 1996, Public Technology, Inc., 1301 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW, Washington, DC  20004-1793; (800) 852-4934.</P>
<P>Presents case studies of  ten communities that have demonstrated administrative, fiscal, and policy tools that can be used by other communities to implement sustainable development initiatives.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Cohousing: A Contemporary Approach to Housing Ourselves</I></B>, 1988, Habitat Press/Ten Speed Press.  ISBN 0-89815-306-9.</P>
<P>Introduces the concept of cohousing and reviews eight cohousing projects.  Offers useful information on creating cohousing, including the development process and design considerations.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Collaborative Communities: Cohousing, Central Living, And Other New Forms Of Housing With </I></B><B><I>Shared Facilities</I></B>, 1991, Van Nostrand Reinhold.  ISBN 0-442-23785-5.</P>
<P>Reviews and evaluates a diversity of housing types that provide the advantages of community while ensuring the privacy of individual homes.  The author focuses on housing where residents take the initiative to plan and manage their neighborhoods and ad





dress the issues in and obstacles to developing living communities.  The book offers information about developments specially designed for families, working parents,  singles, and the elderly, many of which feature the sharing of common facilities such as





 dining, child care, workshops, and libraries.  It also profiles case studies of  successful Dutch, Danish, and Swedish cohousing models.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Community Energy Workbook: A Guide to Building a Sustainable Economy</I></B>, 1995, Rocky Mountain Institute, 1739 Snowmass Creek Road, Snowmass, CO  81654; (970) 927-3851.  ISBN 1-881071-04-9.</P>
<P>Outlines a step-by-step process community groups can follow to create an energy action plan.  This comprehensive approach promotes sustainable energy practices that protect the environment, use less energy, and create a healthier economy.  Includes mor





e than 50 examples of energy-saving strategies and programs proven successful by communities.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Creating Successful Communities:  A Guidebook to Growth Management Strategies</I></B>, 1990, Island Press.  ISBN 1-55963-014-0.</P>
<P>Offers guidelines for developing workable action plans for restoring distinctiveness and livability to communities.  Provides strategies for effective participation in growth-management decision making, discusses how to implement growth-management stra





tegies to protect and enhance natural resources, and describes necessary steps to build and maintain an effective non-profit organization dedicated to growth management and the protection of community assets. </P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Earth in The Balance</I></B>, 1992, Penguin Books.  ISBN 0-395-57821-3.</P>
<P>Vice President Al Gore presents compelling and overwhelming evidence of the global environmental crisis and offers strategic recommendations for re-thinking our relationship with the environment and for taking positive steps to preserve the earth&#146;





s delicate balance.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Ecological Design</I></B>, 1996, Island Press.  ISBN 1-55963-389-1.</P>
<P>The authors present the idea that the world and humanity can be reunited if design is based on ecology.  Ecological design, which the authors define as the marriage of nature and technology, is possible at all levels to create revolutionary buildings, 





landscapes, cities, and technologies.  The book presents design principles to build a more efficient, less toxic, healthier and more sustainable world.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>For the Common Good: Redirecting the Economy Toward Community, the Environment, and a </I></B><B><I>Sustainable Future</I></B><I>, </I>1989, Beacon Press.  ISBN 0-8070-4703-1.</P>
<P> </P>
<P>Demonstrates how our growth-oriented, industrial economy has lead to environmental disaster and offers a new paradigm for economics, public policy, and social ethics.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Housing Without Houses</I></B>, 1991, Van Nostrand Reinhold.  ISBN 0-442-00161-4.</P>
<P>Presents a wide range of innovative concepts and practical methods for housing, as well as examples of actual projects, to illustrate that relying on efficient practices in conditions with scarce resources and high demand will promote, rather than hind





er, spontaneity and incremental development.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Livable Cities</I></B><B>:</B><B><I> A Grass-Roots Guide to Rebuilding Urban</I></B><B> </B><B><I>America</I></B>, 1980, Holt, Reinhard and Winston.  ISBN 0-03-056291-0.</P>
<P>Discusses how citizens across America are joining together  to restore and revitalize their respective communities without the benefit of federal or state programs and without dependency on city planning.   The author presents success stories on establ





ishing an action group, completing a neighborhood plan, enlisting official support, and securing funds. </P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Our Common Future: The World Commission on Environment and Development</I></B>, 1987, Oxford University Press.  ISBN 0-19-282080-x.</P>
<P>Discusses the importance of  uniting the economy and ecology, so that we can take responsibility for environmental damage, as well as for the policies that cause that damage.  Includes chapters on common concerns; common challenges, such as population 





and human resources, food security, species and ecosystems, energy, and industry; and common endeavors, which includes proposals for institutional and legal change.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Regenerative Design for Sustainable Development</I></B>, 1994, John Wiley &amp; Sons, Inc.   ISBN 0-471-55582.</P>
<P>Offers a blueprint for implementing change to reverse damage to the environment.  Describes how to regenerate our resources rather than simply consuming them and discarding the waste.  Emphasizes proven regenerative practices for water use, land use, e





nergy use, and building design.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Rural America at the Crossroads: Networking for the Future</I></B>, 1991, U.S. Congress, Office of Technology Assessment.  Available from Superintendent of Documents, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington, DC  20402. </P>
<P>Explores the role that communication technologies can play in securing rural America&#146;s future and develops several policy strategies and options to encourage such development. </P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Rural By Design: Maintaining Small Town Character</I></B>, 1994, American Planning Association, 1313 East 60th Street, Chicago, IL  60637.  ISBN 0-918268-86-7.</P>
<P>Provides answers to commonly asked questions about creative rural planning techniques, including alternative scenarios for conservation and development, implementation techniques, and examples of a wide variety of residential and commercial projects th





at have utilized creative design techniques.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Rural Environmental Planning For Sustainable Communities</I></B>, 1991, Island Press, ISBN 1-55963-024-8.</P>
<P>Discusses the process of environmental planning for rural areas and
small towns.  Serves as a planning tool to help communities set goals
through public discussion; survey natural resources; create plans that
are environmentally, politically, and financial
ly feasible; and ensure that plans will protect the environment, promote economic diversity, and preserve local culture.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Saving Cities Saving Money: Environmental Strategies That Work</I></B>, 1992, Resource Renewal Institute, Building 1055, Fort Cronkhite, Sausalito, CA  94965.  ISBN 0-932857-08-6.</P>
<P>Presents useful ideas to help communities extend resources, improve environmental quality, and save money by promoting the efficient use of energy, water, materials, and land, and by recycling.  Presents success stories of communities that have become 





self-reliant, curbed urban sprawl, and inspired their residents to strive for a sustainable future.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Self-Reliant Cities: Energy and the Transformation of Urban America</I></B>, 1982, Sierra Club Books, Dept. SA, P.O. Box 7959, San Francisco, CA  94120-7959; (800) 935-1056.  ISBN 0-87156-309-6.</P>
<P>Investigates historical patterns of urban energy use and discusses how today&#146;s communities 
can survive under rising energy costs and resource shortages.  </P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>State of The World</I></B>, 1996, Worldwatch Institute.  Available from WW Norton &amp; Company, 500 Fifth Avenue, New York, NY  10110; (212) 354-5500.  ISBN 0-393-31339-5.</P>
<P>The flagship publication of the Worldwatch Institute, an environmental research organization that analyzes data from many fields, focusing on the relationship between the global economy and its environmental supports, this book presents the most curren





t, authoritative policy analysis available.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Strategies for Rural Competitiveness: Policy Options for State Governments</I></B>, 1993, Council of Governors&#146; Policy Advisors, 400 North Capitol Street, Suite 390, Washington, DC  20001.</P>
<P>Focuses on strategies of state governments, working in concert with community leadership, to improve rural competitiveness.  It includes chapters on the competitive challenge of rural economies, rationales for public intervention, state economic develo





pment policies and rural competitiveness, strategies for rural competitiveness, and the CGPA process for setting priorities.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Sustainable America: A New Consensus for Prosperity,
Opportunity, and a Healthy Environment </I></B><B><I>for the Future</I></B>, 1996, The President&#146;s Council on Sustainable Development (PCSD).  Available from the U.S. Government Printi

ng Office, Superintendent of Documents, Mail Stop cc, Washington, DC  20402-9328.  ISBN 0-16-048529-0.</P>
<P>Presents PCSD&#146;s recommendations to the President for a national sustainable development action strategy.  The book includes chapters on strengthening communities, natural resources stewardship, U.S. population and sustainability, and international





 leadership.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><I></I> <B><I>Sustainable Cities:  Concepts and Strategies for Eco-City Development</I></B>, 1992, Eco-Home Media, 4344 Russell Avenue, Los Angeles, CA  90027; (213) 664-7706.  ISBN 0-9633511-0-9.</P>
<P>Leading experts from their respective fields present concepts and strategies for ecological city design that include ecological design principles, planning techniques, resource management, community relations, sustainable technologies, construction tec





hniques, economic strategies, and more.  The book shows how urban development and the environment can coexist in a successful partnership that will result in better air quality, cleaner water, more nutritious food, less commuting time, quieter and more na





ture-oriented surroundings, a richer community life, less urban stress, and improved health for the people who live and work in cities.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Sustainable Communities: A New Design Synthesis for Cities, Suburbs and Towns</I></B>, 1986, Sierra Club Books, Dept. SA, P.O. Box 7959, San Francisco, CA  94120-7959; (800) 935-1056.  ISBN 0-87156-800-4.</P>
<P>Two experts on appropriate technology present a practical vision of how different types of American communities can make the transition to a way to life that encourages sustainability, reduces resource waste, balances consumption and production, and pr





oduces long-term social and ecological health.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>A Sustainable World: Defining and measuring sustainable development</I></B>, 1994, International Center for the Environment and Public Policy, P.O. Box 189040, Sacramento, CA  95818; (916) 442-2472.</P>
<P>Contributors to this book discuss, from a variety of perspectives, what &#145;sustainability&#146; and &#145;sustainable development&#146; really mean and how we know whether we&#146;re moving toward a sustainable future. </P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><I></I> <B><I>Sustaining the Earth: Choosing Consumer Products That Are Safe For You, Your Family, and the </I></B><B><I>Earth</I></B>, 1994, Hearst Books.  ISBN 0-688-12335-x.</P>
<P>Presents information to help the reader assess the environmental pros and cons of everyday products, including food, appliances, and cleaning products.  It tells the difference between products with real environmental benefits and those with misleading





 green hype.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<LI><P><B><I>Visions For A New American Dream: Process, Principles, And An Ordinance To Plan And </I></B><B><I>Design Small Communities</I></B>, 1994, American Planning Association, 1313 East 60th Street, Chicago, IL  60637.  ISBN 1-884829-00-7</P>
<P>Provides guidelines to plan and design small communities, including hamlets, villages, and neighborhoods in the urban fringe whether they are new or to be retrofitted.  The author provides definitions and characteristics of a small community, analyzes 





the problems of the past to better plan and design the future, discusses creating a common vision, analyzes the potentials for small community design, and offers ten principles in designing a small community.  The book includes generic recommendations, wh





ich can be adapted and varied to suit a particular site.  </P>
</UL>

<P><BR></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P> 
<H3><A NAME="Articles"></A> Recommended Articles</H3>
