<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <TITLE>Cities and Counties: Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#EEEEEE" link="#0033CC" vlink="#555555" alink="#00EE00">

<I><A HREF="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/ss/pti/">Cities &amp; Counties</A></I><p>

<B>INTRODUCTION</B><BR>

<hr>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="30" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="400">

As the municipalities of the world grow and develop, they
contribute to the depletion of natural resources and increased
pollution to the air, water, and land.  As if an enormous debt
were suddenly falling due, the United States - and the rest of
the wold - is discovering that our unfettered consumption of
the earth's natural resources and nonrenewable energy sources to
support economic growth polluted our air, water, and land, visibly
damaging our environment.  This damage is occurring and is
exacting the heavy price of global climate deterioration, loss of
biodiversity, and dangerous levels of hazardous and solid waste
accumulation.<P>
The conventional view of competition between economic growth and
environmental quality must be changed through public policy,
management, and investment practices.  To maintain the critical
balance between a healthy economy and a healthy environment,
economic growth and environmental quality must be treated as
complementary objectives.  This balanced perspective is essential
to "sustain" our communities.  Cities and counties envision
sustainability in their future.  Local governments hold a unique
position as leaders in sustainability - they have the interest
to promote sustainable development, the facilities to act as
"sustainability laboratories," the authority to initiate positive
change, and the flexibility to tailor programs to specific local
circumstances. <P>
At the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992, countries took up
the battle cry for sustainability, calling for local government
changes that would tie economic growth to environmental
protection.  Public Technology, Inc., (PTI) played a major role in
the event's planning and was a highly visible voice for U.S. local
governments during the summit.  Since then, PTI's support and
promotion of new technologies and management approaches for local
government sustainability have grown dramatically.<P>
Today PTI's local government members, which include the well-known
network - the Urban Consortium (UC) - work to research and
promote sustainable technologies and implement sustainable
development strategies to address the pressing local government
problems and needs.  A goal of PTI's local government program for
sustainability is twofold:  (1) to clarify the term
"sustainability" and obtain a common definition among communities,
and (2) to promote local government commitments to the principles
of sustainability and to strategies that use local government
resources wisely.  The goal represents a practical vision for the
future.  Clearly, "business as usual" is not sustainable.<P>
Consumption practices cannot be reversed overnight; sustainability
planning is an ongoing, dynamic activity requiring careful
development, nurturing, implementation, and review.  Sustainable
development is a trial-and-error proposition.  Local governments
can be - and in many areas, are - leaders to refine the
vision for a sustainable community.  This leadership requires
finding tools and creating working programs with clear benefits at
local, national, and global levels.  A mayor of a large urban city
remarked over four years ago that, while the term "sustainability"
is not entirely clear - nor without controversy - the
concept of an effective and sustainable integration of economics
and the environment is one that a local government can both
understand and practice.<P>
Cities and counties own, operate, and manage large numbers of
buildings and facilities, as well as vehicle fleets and
mass-transit systems; they design, plan, finance, and operate
major water, wastewater, and solid- and hazardous waste management
systems; they enact local plans and policies that affect
residential, commercial, and industrial development as well as
land-use and transportation choices.  Local governments have vital
interests in improving and maintaining the quality of the air,
water and land resources essential to our economic and
environmental well-being and quality of life.  Most cities and
counties will implement sustainability measures incrementally and
promote them in meaningful ways.  The vision of sustainability is
not limited to unique places; communities across the country are
involving residents, government officials, and businesspeople in
dialogue and action toward the goal of fostering sustainable
development.  Citizens from all social and economic groups should
take part in decision-making.  It is critical to their healthy
survival.<P>
Numerous cities and counties are designing and implementing
sustainable plans.  Others are in the midst of identifying
indicators of progress or benchmarks of sustainability; many
programs are not specifically labeled as "sustainable" but are
consistent with the vision of sustainable communities.  This study
examines how various governmental policies, institutional
configurations, and intergovernmental relationships are enabling
local governments to identify and achieve sustainability
objectives.<P>
This document employs a case-study approach to characterize and
evaluate the "tools" used by 10 different communities to implement
sustainable actions.  PTI will use the results to help local
government managers and decision-makers learn from each other and
utilize policy tools in pursuing sustainable development
initiatives.<P>
The case studies are being distributed nationally and
internationally, attracting recognition to the selected
jurisdictions.  By emphasizing replicability, these examples
address a range of policy actions to encourage and assist other
local jurisdictions to orient programs to sustain the needs of
citizens and involve them directly.  With effective links among
policy, management, and technology, and with a strong
customer-citizen orientation, local governments can incorporate
sustainability into their own development plans.<P>

<B>APPROACH</B><P>
The purpose of these case studies is to demonstrate
administrative, fiscal, and policy tools that local jurisdictions
can use to implement and maintain sustainability initiatives. 
Developing the case studies involved looking at both "the forest"
and individual "trees."    It was first necessary to identify a
set of sustainable communities - the forest - and then
identify tools used to implement specific programs in each of the
jurisdictions - the trees.<P>
<b>For this study, sustainability is defined as the ongoing presence
of government-sponsored programs in areas that contribute to
economic growth, combined with enlightened long-term planning and
the judicious use of resources.  To begin the research, PTI
conducted a data search and created a Sustainable Communities
Database including descriptors of over 1450 initiatives in 744
U.S. cities and counties.  The database includes 10 program
categories:  energy efficiency, renewable energy, transportation
efficiency, air pollution, economic development, sustainable
development plans, water conservation, waste management, pollution
prevention, and land use.  A weighted, multi-attribute approach
was then used to identify city and county governments that are
leaders in incorporating sustainability into their development
priorities.  Four principle factors were weighed:  (1) diversity
of programs, (2) total number of programs, (3) economic planning
and development activities, and (4) sustainable development
planning.  In the end, 10 communities were chosen as the
sustainability cases.  The selected communities vary in size,
economic circumstances, and geographic distribution.  They also
vary considerably with respect to level of development of
sustainability programs.  Some of the selected jurisdictions have
demonstrated a commitment to local sustainability for a decade or
more, while others have begun sustainability programs more
recently or are in the early stages of creating policies and
programs.</b><P>
Members of PTI's Urban Energy and Environmental Task Force were
contacted in each of the selected jurisdictions to help provide
additional information on their home jurisdiction and particular
program.  In particular, PTI contacts helped identify specific
programs and noteworthy "tool" applications.  PTI's approach was,
first, to identify 10 sustainable case-study jurisdictions, and,
second, to identify a specific program within each jurisdiction
that exemplifies creative use of governmental tools.  A last step
used extensive dialogue with local contacts to obtain structured
information on project administration, finance, barriers,
stakeholders, and policy tools utilized.<BR><p>

<IMG SRC="MAP.gif" ALT="Case Study Sites (US Map)" ALIGN=top WIDTH="500" HEIGHT="290">
<p>
<hr>
<B>TOOLS FOR SUSTAINABILITY PLANNING AND PRACTICE<BR>
</B><BR>
As the following case studies demonstrate, local governments use a
broad array of policy, fiscal, and administrative tools to create
and maintain locally directed sustainability initiatives. 
Although  sustainability goals often depart from traditional local
management strategies, the basic tools employed are remarkably
similar to those commonly used to advance the entire spectrum of
local policy and management objectives.  <P>
The sustainability toolbox contains such conventional items as
taxes, fees, grants, ordinances, and regulations.  Less
conventional - but increasingly attractive - economic
development strategies include incentive programs, public-private
partnerships and strategic collaborations, and enterprise zones. 
These methods can also encourage nongovernmental organizations to
be partners in sustainable development activities.  The tools can
be placed into four major groups:  monetary payments, restrictions
and penalties, goods and services, and legal protection.    <P>

<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=100%>
<TR VALIGN=top><TH COLSPAN=4>EXHIBIT 1 - EXAMPLES OF POLICY TOOLS
AVAILABLE TO LOCAL GOVERNMENTS</TH></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=top><b>Monetary Payments</b><P>
<font size="-1">

Grants<BR>
  	- formula<br>
  	- project<br>
  	- block<br>
Procurement<BR>
Research Funding<BR>
Income Support<BR>
Land Acquisition</font></TD>

<TD VALIGN=top><b>Restrictions and Penalties   </b><P>
<font size="-1">

Regulations<BR>
Ordinances<BR>
Standards
  	- technology<br>
  	- performance<br>
  	- input<br>
Fees<BR>
Zoning<BR>
Development  Guidelines<BR>
Emission Controls<BR>

</font></TD>

<TD valign=top><B>Goods & Services</B><P>
<font size="-1">

Capital Improvements<BR>
Demonstrations<BR>
Technical Assistance<BR>
Insurance<BR>
Education/Information<BR>
Advertising<BR>
Government                   Cooperation<BR>
Property Management<BR>
Partnerships</font></TD>

<TD valign=top><b>Legal Protection</b><P>
<font size="-1">

Development Rights<BR>
Conservation                  Easements<BR>
Loan Support<BR>
	- guarantees<br>
  	- forgiveness<br>
	- subsidies<br>
Franchise<BR>
Exemptions<BR>
Price Supports<BR>
Enterprise Zones
</font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER><FONT SIZE="-1">Source:  Lester M. Salamon, et al., <I>Beyond
Privatization.</I> Washington, DC: Urban Institute Press, 1989</FONT><P>
<I>Monetary Payments</I><BR>
Governments often pay individuals and organizations in order to
promote certain policies and practices.  In most cases, these
inducements require the recipient to perform specified activities.
 Such payments frequently take the form of grants and
procurements.  For example, state and local governments often
administer federal grants-in-aid - funding from the federal
government targeted toward specific programs.  Recent
Congressional trends suggest a shift to block grants, giving state
and local governments broad discretion to allocate grant funds
according to local policy decisions rather than federal mandates. 
Procurements use the government's fiscal resources to help create
or expand the market for valued products or activities.  Other
monetary tools used to influence prices and consumption include
awards and prizes, subsidies, and rebates.  All of these tools are
used with the assumption that valued outcomes will not occur
unless induced by the promise of monetary gain.<P>
For a number of the case-study jurisdictions,  monetary incentives
as an important program element.  In Chattanooga,  the local
transportation authority received grants from a number of federal
and local sources.  The grants were used to fund procurement
contracts to promote electric transit vehicle manufacturing and
market expansion.  These contracts helped to motivate
entrepreneurial investors to provide the initial capital for the
manufacture of electric buses. In San Jose, procurement strategies
that encourage recycled-products packages condition markets in
ways that achieve public objectives.<P>
<I>Restrictions and Penalties</I><BR>
Governments often employ regulations, ordinances, and fees, more
generally categorized as "mandates," to pursue specific policy
objectives.  While many other tools offer incentives for desired
outcomes, this class of tools establishes disincentives (usually
financial) for engaging in practices with undesired outcomes. 
Ordinances, regulations, and standards define norms, and failure
to comply with them often results in sanctions.  Fees and
penalties are charged to discourage certain activities that run
counter to policy objectives, or to offset their costs.  The
issuance of standards or zoning requirements delineates a range of
appropriate activities and forbids or restricts other activities. 
Most restrictions and penalties are created with the assumption
that a certain action should be required of all individuals or
organizations.  Used alone, restrictions and penalties typically
result in adversarial relationships, making compliance enforcement
necessary.<P>
In Chittenden County, communities are developing outdoor-lighting
standards that may restrict or prohibit the use of some lighting
technologies, require additional shielding equipment, or otherwise
limit the range of lighting options.  In Boulder, a solar-access
ordinance created restrictions on new development that help to
preserve and protect buildings' current and future access to
sunlight.    <P>
<I>Provision of Goods and Services</I><BR>
Another important role of government to provide goods and
services, especially the latter.  Government loans, vouchers,
cooperative agreements, and partnerships may facilitate the
acquisition of resources required by the private sector in the
pursuit of projects that promote local initiatives.  Advertising,
labeling, education, demonstrations, technical assistance, and
public service announcements are informational tools that the
government often contributes.  Insurance, mediation, investigation
of complaints, and inspection and testing are all services that
government can provide to entice private-sector cooperation on
sustainability issues and to address grass-roots concerns about
potential problems.<P>
Several of the programs studied offer services to promote
sustainability.  Northampton County is making capital investments
to facilitate sustainable economic development. Chittenden County
is developing an informational package that will provide technical
information on outdoor lighting.  Chattanooga, Metro-Dade County,
and Metropolitan Philadelphia all use public-private partnerships
to advance their programs' goals.  Austin provided building
contractors with training to demonstrate the benefits of energy
efficiency and familiarize them with new technologies. <p>

<I>Legal protection</I><BR>
The fourth category of tools the government uses to promote
programs is legal protection for individuals and organizations. 
Protection beyond that associated with normal property rights is
sometimes required to promote various policies and practices,
including those involved in sustainable development.  Benefits are
not immediately apparent in certain economic activities and may
face a hostile business environment.  Such activities may require
governmental nurturing or protection.  Loan guarantees, loans with
certain types of forgiveness, and loans with subsidies are all
tools that fall within this category.  Exemptions from legal
requirements may also be used by local government to reduce risk,
lower costs, stimulate business, and provide tax relief.<P>
Legal protections have been employed by some case-study
jurisdictions to promote sustainability.  To promote energy-saving
home improvements and appliance upgrades, Austin's Environmental
and Conservation Services Department provides support for
energy-efficiency loans in the form of subsidies and guarantees. 
Through an innovative permit system, Boulder confers solar
development rights to businesses and home owners to protect
investments in renewable energy.<P>
   <BR>
Each of the tools described here has benefits and limitations. 
The variety, however, is sufficiently broad to accommodate
different needs and individual circumstances.  Successful
sustainable development efforts give careful consideration to
available government tools and recognize their limitations.  The
choice of tools substantially impacts a program's initiation and
long-term efficacy.  Different tools require different
administrative skills, financial cycles, requirements for
political leadership and support, and organizational
relationships.  The case studies that follow demonstrate how
various tools provide unique pathways to the same overall
objective - sustainability.<p>
<B>SYNOPSIS OF CASE STUDY PROGRAMS</B><P>
<B>Home Energy Loan Program  -  Austin, Texas.</B>  The
program eliminates the initial cost barrier of installing energy
efficient equipment by offering residential customers a
zero-interest or low-interest loan. Between 80 and 85 percent of
the program's customers pay less in monthly utility bills and loan
payments combined than they paid for electricity alone before
making improvements. The program offset 20 megawatts of additional
generating capacity from 1993 to 1991.  <I>Tools:  loan support,
demonstrations, technical assistance</I><P>
<B>Solar-Access Ordinance  -  Boulder, Colorado.</B> 
Since 1982, the city of Boulder has had in place a solar-access
ordinance.  The ordinance protects solar access of existing
buildings by limiting the amount of shadow new development may
cast on neighboring property.  It encourages adoption of solar
technologies in new buildings by requiring buildings to be
oriented in a manner that maximizes access to passive solar
energy.  <I>Tools:  ordinance, education/information, development
rights</I> <P>
<B>Outdoor Lighting Standards  -  Chittenden County,
Vermont.</B>  Vermont's increasing rate of development has
citizens concerned about the visual effects of outdoor lighting on
the night landscape and the night sky.  Chittenden County's
outdoor-lighting initiative will help educate communities about
solutions to lighting programs.  The initiative has selected three
case-study communities and is developing outdoor-lighting
standards for these municipalities.  Already, the program has
sparked interest in other communities and captured attention from
the state of Vermont.  The program's benefits will include reduced
energy consumption and preservation the beautiful night views so
valued by Vermonters.  <I>Tools:  standards, research funding,
technical assistance</I><p>
<B>Public/Private Partnerships in Electric Bus Development
 -  Chattanooga/Hamilton County, Tennessee</B>.  The local
transit authority for the city of Chattanooga and Hamilton County
formed an innovative public-private partnership to develop, build,
test, and operate electric transit vehicles (ETVs) and ETV systems
in downtown Chattanooga.  Since 1991, ten electric buses have gone
in service on a downtown shuttle route, a local nonprofit
organization has been launched to promote research and provide
information, and a company has been formed to manufacture electric
buses.  The program's "Living Laboratory" brings participants
together to develop ETVs and share their discoveries worldwide. 
Program benefits include reduced congestion on downtown streets,
reduced air emissions, and more than 30 new manufacturing jobs. 
<I>Tools:  grants, procurement, research funding, capital
improvements, demonstrations, partnership</I><p>
<B>Planning a Resource- and Energy-Efficient Community: Jordan
Commons  -  Metro-Dade County, Florida.</B>  Metro-Dade County,
in partnership with an area nonprofit organization, is developing
a $17 million, 200-home model community for low-income families
that were left vulnerable to homelessness by Hurricane Andrew. 
The project will feature energy-efficient technologies and
incorporate recycling, composting, landscaping, and
water-conservation methods, emphasizing the corresponding energy
and financial savings.  Educational programs will reinforce the
use of resource-saving technologies, building community awareness
of the importance of conservation and the associated cost savings
each household can enjoy.  <I>Tools:  education, procurement,
demonstrations, partnership</I><P>
<B>Growth Management through the "GreenPlan Alliance"
 -  Metropolitan Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.</B>  While
preserving open space in urban areas is only one of many issues of
sustainability, it is an especially important one to metropolitan
Philadelphia.  Experts project that by the year 2020, the
Philadelphia region will lose 173,000 acres of open space to
development - an area more than twice the size of the city of
Philadelphia.  The loss of open space reduces recreational
opportunity, makes the region less attractive to employers and
workers, and undermines the region's environment through reduced
air and water quality and increased flooding risks.  The
GreenSpace Alliance (GSA) works with local governments and brings
together local and regional leaders interested in the protection
of open space in the Philadelphia area.  The GSA is sponsoring a
series of demonstration projects, building community partnerships,
and developing a comprehensive open
space preservation plan.  <I>Tools:  development guidelines,
zoning, government cooperation, partnership</I><p>
<B>Building an Eco-Industrial Park  -  Northampton County,
Virginia.</B>  Northampton County is reversing its economic
decline through a unique Sustainable Development Action Strategy. 
Since its conception in September 1993, the strategy has won
national acclaim as a model of comprehensive public-private
partnership for small-town, rural development.  One outcome of the
strategy is the Port of  Cape Charles Sustainable Technologies
Industrial Park, a beacon for environmentally friendly business. 
<I>Tools:  capital improvements, grants, land acquisition,
government cooperation, enterprise zones</I><P>
<B>Resolution for Procurement and Use of Recycled and
Environmentally Sensitive Products  -  Phoenix, Arizona.</B> 
As a collector of large quantities of recyclable materials, the
city of Phoenix developed an interest in the availability of
markets for recyclables and the development of products using
recycled materials.  In 1992, the city passed a procurement
resolution that set guidelines for the purchase of recycled paper,
the use of recycled tires, maximization of compost and mulch use,
and use of products such as recycled plastic park benches.  The
resolution also called for the creation of a formal pollution
prevention program.  <I>Tools:  procurement,
education/information, property management</I><p>

<B>City Challenge Program  -  Portland, Oregon.</B> 
Nicknamed "One Percent for Energy," Portland's City Energy
Challenge program uses a city-imposed fee of one percent on all
city government energy bills to finance an energy management
program for city facilities.  In its first four and a half years,
the program has identified a potential annual savings of over $1.2
million in more than 70 facilities.  To date, the program has
already completed projects that will save taxpayers almost
$700,000 per year.  <I>Tools:  fees, capital improvements,
technical assistance, property management,
education/information</I><p>
<B>Integrated Waste Management Program and Source Reduction
and Recycling Procurement Policy  -  San Jose, California.</B> 
Through its Integrated Waste Management Program and its Source
Reduction and Recycling Procurement Policy, San Jose has become a
national leader in stimulating markets for recycled products.  The
San Jose strategy requires that the city consider the recycled
content and recyclability of products and packaging in its
procurement decisions. San Jose wisely recognizes that
discouraging discrimination against recycled products speeds
acceptance of such products in the marketplace, reinforcing
municipal recycling programs.  <I>Tools:  technical assistance,
procurement, education/information, government cooperation</I>
<P>
<B>SUSTAINABILITY AT THE LOCAL LEVEL:  LESSONS LEARNED</B><P>
The case studies confirm that local officials and initiatives have
a vital role in marking a path to sustainability that others will
follow.  Local jurisdictions across the country are demonstrating
that sustainability on a global scale can be achieved one city or
county at a time.  The studies also confirm that different
jurisdictions can and must tailor sustainability initiatives to
meet their own needs and circumstances in ways that yield
long-term economic, social, and environmental benefits..  <P>
Different tools will result in different pathways to
sustainability, but some lessons seem applicable across divergent
circumstances.  Six patterns seem to emerge from the case studies:
<P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Local government sustainability initiatives can result in
robust markets and create private sector allies; <BR>
	<LI>Sustainability initiatives should be pursued using a
combination of tools rather than a single tool or a
one-dimensional strategy;<BR>
	<LI>Local-level sustainability activities should be
administered through a "champion" or a point of focus, not left to
a committee;<BR>
	<LI>Local government can effectively use innovative and
"off-line" approaches in financing projects; <BR>
	<LI>Local government should identify and recruit
nongovernmental, nonprofit partners before a project is started,
not after concerns are raised; and<BR>
	<LI>Joint administration is not necessarily impossible, or
even impractical.<P>
</UL>
<I>1. Creating Private-Sector Allies and Markets</I><P>
Instead of creating regulatory, or "command and control" burdens,
many of the case-study projects actually created private-sector
and citizen allies through their activities.  In many cases, new
modes of operation were created between government and the private
sector that minimized adversity and worked like partnerships or
strategic collaborations.   The <B>Austin Electric Utility's Home
Energy Loan</B> staff worked closely with the local building
industry to train and collaborate with private-sector building
contractors on new technologies and procedures.  Austin Home
Energy Program staff also worked in partnership with a local
lending institution to provide efficient loan processing and
reduce the city's loan guarantee exposure. In Tennessee, <B>the
Chattanooga Area Regional Transportation Authority</B> (CARTA) has
engaged in a close and effective working relationship with an
electric bus manufacturer, as well as a private nonprofit research
and information-dissemination organization.<P>
In other case studies, new markets for private-sector products
were created to enhance sustainability.  In the <B>city of
Phoenix, a recycled-products resolution</B> encouraged and
acknowledged significant private- sector participation in the
procurement of recycled goods and other products that decrease
environmental degradation. In <B>Metro-Dade County, the Jordan
Commons project</B> creates a local market for manufacturing
companies to increase sales in energy-efficient and renewable
energy technologies, and to help condition national markets for
similar technologies.  The <B>Integrated Waste Management program
in San Jose</B> has helped demonstrate the feasibility of recycled
products.  The demand for good-quality recycled products has
pressured vendors to adjust standards in order to maintain their
contracts with the city, paving the way for expanded networks.  In
each case, sustainability initiatives were pursued with market
conditioning and close cooperation with the private sector, rather
than imposed through command-and-control restrictions.<P>

<I>2. Strategically Combining Tools</I><P>
Just as diversifying investments can strengthen a portfolio, using
a combination of policy, administrative, and fiscal
tools - rather than relying on a one-dimensional
approach - can strengthen a sustainability project. 
<B>Austin's</B> home energy program combined an energy code, loan
support, a training and demonstration program for building
contractors, and a partnership with a local bank.  The loan
support provided the incentive for homeowners to make
energy-saving home improvements and purchase upgraded appliances. 
The home improvements provided increased business for building
contractors.  As the contractors became more familiar with new
technology through training provided by the city, they became
supportive of energy code revisions by the government.  Each tool
was supported by the other tools.  Limiting use to a single tool,
such as an ordinance, may have resulted in resistance to the
program.  In <B>Chittenden, tools included technical information
and lighting standards</B>.  To date, little research has been
done on outdoor lighting to provide guidance to jurisdictions. 
The regional planning commission in Burlington is in the process
of developing technical information in partnership with the
Lighting Research Center of Troy, New York.  By the end of the
project, three communities will have developed model lighting
ordinances for their communities and other jurisdictions
nationwide.  <P>
San Jose bolstered its Source Reduction and Recycling Procurement
Policy with a focused market development strategy for recycled
materials.  San Jose's Integrated Waste Management Program
emphasizes technical assistance, product testing, and public
education to facilitate citywide acceptance and use.  Metro-Dade
developed a partnership with a capital improvement project to
develop Jordan Commons and bolstered the project's implementation
through education programs and the opportunity for manufacturers
of energy-efficient and renewable energy technologies to showcase
leading-edge products.<p>
<I>3. Designating a Champion or a Point of
Focus</I><P>
Sustainable development initiatives are inherently
cross-disciplinary, involving the integration of previously
distinct organizations.  Sustainable development requires policies
and management approaches that coordinate organizations.  This
results in concerns for "turf" and organizational autonomy, making
it difficult to coordinate the work of different agencies.  There
should be a coordinator or designated "champion" to work with the
different agencies, the external finance community, development
professionals, industry, and local citizens to "make things
happen."  For instance, in <B>Northampton, Virginia</B>, a grant
through the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality's Coastal
Resources enabled the Director of Sustainable Development to be
hired by Northampton's Board of Supervisors.  <B>Portland</B>
hired an energy management coordinator for city facilities through
its <B>City Challenge program. </B>Similarly, in <B>San Jose,</B>
a staff member acts as recycling coordinator to source new
recycled products, research markets for recycling of city surplus
property, and generally enhance the city's in-house recycling
program.  In each case, participants express doubt that the
cross-disciplinary, multi-organizational projects could have
succeeded without a champion of sustainability.<P>
<I>4. Using Innovative Approaches to Financing </I><P>
Sustainability initiatives often require proponents to think
"outside of the box" when it comes to program financing.  Rarely
are programs financed as budget increments or line items.  It is
somewhat unusual for a government office to impose fees upon
itself, yet this is just what happened in Portland.  Nicknamed
"One Percent for Energy," <B>Portland's</B> City Challenge program
used a city-imposed fee of 1 percent on all city government energy
bills to hire an energy-management coordinator for city
facilities.  The fee contains an incentive feature, however, in
that a portion of the money saved through efficiency measures is
returned to the participating agency.  The county of
<B>Northampton</B> cut its spending in order to create a reserve
of public funds to begin construction of a Sustainable
Technologies Industrial Park.  Northampton also leveraged funding
from a variety of state, federal, and private foundation grants.
In <B>Chattanooga</B>, CARTA leveraged a large percentage of its
project's funding from the U.S. Department of Transportation,
along with state and city funds. <P>
In <B>Metro-Dade County, the Jordan Commons project</B> was
financed in part through corporate sponsorship.  Specifically,
Metro-Dade partnered with the local affiliate of Habitat for
Humanity, which in turn utilized the national organization's
extensive fund raising ability to designate a corporate sponsor
for each home in the project.  Funding for the <B>City of Austin
Home Energy Loan Program</B> involves three independent entities:
the City's Environmental and Conservation Service Department
(ECSD), the municipal utility, and a private lending institution. 
Specifically, the utility provides program funding to ECSD, which
in turn uses the funding to "buy down" the bank's market
based interest rate.  Innovative financing is clearly a key to
initiating and maintaining local-scale sustainability programs. 
These studies suggest that a great deal of flexibility is
available to city and county governments willing to enter into
partnerships with nongovernment organizations and private lending
institutions.<BR>
 <BR>
<I>5. Forming Joint Administrative Partnerships</I><P>
In <B>Metropolitan Philadelphia</B>, the Pennsylvania
Environmental Council became involved in the area of "growth
management."  This interest ultimately led to the creation of the
<B>GreenSpace Alliance</B> (GSA), which includes 5 municipal
governments.  Recognizing that the siting of high-density
development is often a barrier to formulation of open-space plans,
the GSA recommends that jurisdictions bring together concerned
residents, local officials, and developers to prevent adversarial
relationships from forming.  In <B>Northampton</B>, the interest
of numerous grass-roots organizations contributed to the county's
sustainable development plan and the resulting enterprise park. 
The <B>Jordan Commons project in Metro-Dade County</B> was
codeveloped with the Homestead Habitat for Humanity, a
high-profile organization which helped the county to expand the
number and scope of stakeholders and provide a strong measure of
project credibility.  In <B>Phoenix</B>, the recycled-materials
procurement resolution was developed with the participation and
input of key stakeholders, including city managers and procurement
officials who assisted in the writing of the resolution, ensuring
that its goals and guidelines were both aggressive and
achievable.<P>
<I>6.Making Joint Program Administration Work
</I><p>
It is a bureaucratic credo that projects cannot be effectively
managed by more than one organization.  Interdepartmental or
interjurisdictional coordination tends to be viewed as the "crab
grass" of local governance - hard to control and generally
undesirable.  However, almost all jurisdictions in this study have
successfully co-administered sustainability initiatives with
governmental departments or agencies or with nongovernmental
organizations.  For example, <B>Metro-Dade County</B>
co-administers the Jordan Commons housing complex with Habitat for
Humanity, an original project sponsor.  In fact, some of the work
at Jordan Commons involves volunteer coordinators "managing"
county contractors.  In <B>Portland, the Office of Fiscal
Administration</B> successfully "bundled" 46 energy
efficiency upgrades from eight separate bureaus into a larger
financing package for construction of a new police station.  This
fiscal cross-administration resulted in a five-year, 3.8 percent
loan, helping individual bureaus to overcome capital barriers to
sustainability.  In <B>Austin</B>, the city co-administers the
residential energy- efficiency loan program in cooperation with a
private lending institution.  The <B>Chittenden County Regional
Planning Commission</B> is developing model lighting ordinances
applicable to the divergent needs and interests of three
independent communities in Vermont - Burlington, Richmond, and
Shelburne.


</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>
</body>
