<IMG SRC="BOLDRPIC.gif" ALT="Image: Solar House" ALIGN="LEFT"
  WIDTH="148" HEIGHT="220" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <H1>BOULDER, <BR>COLORADO</H1>
  <P><I>&quot;The importance of Boulder's solar-access ordinance is that
  it maintains the potential for using renewable energy in the future.&quot;
  </I></P>
  <P>  <P><IMG SRC="BOLDREMB.gif" ALIGN="right" WIDTH="66" HEIGHT=
  "66" ALT="City of Boulder Emblem" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></P>
  <I>-<FONT SIZE=-1> Peter Pollock, Director of Community
  Planning, City of Boulder </FONT></I></P>
  </BLOCKQUOTE>
  <br clear=all>  <br clear=all>
  
  <P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>ABSTRACT<BR>
  </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=+1><BR>
  Since 19 82, the city of Boulder has had in place a solar-access ordinance.
  The ordinance protects solar access of existing buildings by limiting the
  amount of shadow new development may cast on neighboring property. It also
  encourages adoption of solar technologies in new buildings by requiring
  that buildings be oriented for maximum access to passive solar energy.
  It should be noted that while this case study examines a specific component
  of sustainability, e.g., how to increase a community's access to alternative,
  renewable energy supplies, additional programs pertaining to sustainable
  development in Boulder are listed <A HREF="#otherprog">elsewhere</A>. </FONT>
  
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<hr>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="30" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="400">
<B>SOLAR ACCESS KEEPS ENERGY ALTERNATIVES OPEN</B></P>

<P>Between 1982 and 1995, nearly 8000 residential units were built in Boulder,
Colorado. Because the city recognized the need to provide a sustainable
energy future for its residents, the vast majority of those homes have protected
access to solar energy and its increasingly attractive benefits. Future
residential construction will enjoy the same protection.</P>

<P>Boulder has not always been a leader in solar access. During the late
1970s the city of Boulder, like others across the country, became acutely
aware of its dependence on imported energy sources. In response, city planners
began to explore means to become more self-sufficient. Recognizing that
solar energy was an ample local resource, Boulder decided to take steps
to preserve and protect its buildings' current and future access to sunlight.</P>

<P>To meet this goal, Boulder adopted a solar-access ordinance. The ordinance
was designed to protect solar resource availability in existing buildings
and in new construction, setting area-wide ground rules flexibile enough
to accommodate unique needs of individual situations on a case by case basis.
In order to ensure ease of administration, Boulder developed an ordinance
with many noteworthy features:</P>

<UL>
  <LI><I>No unnecessary regulatory burdens on builders</I>. The city did
  not want to require every building-permit applicant to generate elaborate
  data, nor did it wish to create complex and unfamiliar procedures or prolong
  the time required to secure a permit.<BR>
  </LI>
  <LI><I>Simplicity</I>. The city wanted to develop an ordinance that was
  easily understood and applied.<BR>
  </LI>
  <LI><I>Flexibility</I>. Recognizing a lack of flexibility as a key flaw
  in the solar access ordinances of other cities, Boulder wanted its ordinance
  to feature the latitude necessary to address individual circumstances.<BR>
  </LI>
  <LI><I>Room to learn</I>. Anticipating the continuing evolution of solar
  technology, the city wanted its ordinance provisions to accommodate ever
  newer technologies.<BR>
  </LI>
</UL>

<P><B>Protecting and Promoting Solar Access</B> </P>

<P>Boulder's focus on solar energy stemmed, in part, from its participation
in the Comprehensive Community Energy Management Program, funded by the
U.S. Department of Energy. The program supported a comprehensive audit of
energy use and supply in Boulder, facilitated community participation in
dialogues on energy alternatives, and allowed the creation of an action
plan and an energy advisory board to begin revising the city's land-use
regulations. </P>

<P>In assessing the various available energy alternatives, the city energy
office and other groups concluded that solar energy was the most viable
option for local action. Boulder's long heating season and very sunny climate
make it well suited to solar development. A favorable climate coupled with
various state tax credits for the use of both active and passive solar energy,
made the use of solar technology an ideal way to improve energy sustainability.
Many local planners, builders, and residents already had come to the same
conclusion. Solar-energy use in Boulder was common and growing more popular.</P>

<P>Boulder sought to capitalize on local awareness to encourage further
solar energy development, especially in residential settings. It foresaw
two principal obstacles however. <BR>
First was the potential for more disputes over solar access as new development
undermined the efficacy of existing solar-energy systems on nearby property.
An ordinance would clarify solar access property rights, eliminating this
type of dispute. Interestingly, in researching solar ordinances elsewhere,
Boulder's planners discovered that solar access litigation was only a problem
in jurisdictions lacking protection laws. </P>

<P>The second concern was that the cost of securing protected solar access
on a case-by-case basis kept some people from building additions and installing
energy systems designed to absorb solar radiation. Without the broad protection
of an ordinance, a solar-energy user needed to secure durable agreements
with neighbors in order to guarantee continued access to solar resources.
Forging such agreements was likely to involve fees to engineers, surveyors
and attorneys.</P>

<P>When Boulder finally passed its solar-access ordinance, the greatest
opposition was from the area's building community. The building community
was concerned that the ordinance would lead to untenable limitations on
the design and placement of new buildings. Many developers argued that if
the public truly demanded solar access, the market would provide it. While
most area residents favored Boulder's action some expressed concern about
its proposed limits on tree shading and others opposed the ordinance itself
as unnecessary government interference.</P>

<P>City officials addressed these concerns by encouraging skeptical builders
and residents to consider the solar access issue in a broader context. They
asked the community to compare the modest solar access provisions the city
had proposed to current zoning restrictions and utility easements. In doing
this, they created a link between solar access regulations and widely-accepted
city planning standards and property-use restrictions. Moreover, they drew
attention to the fact that all energy utility customers' interests are served
by solar's reduction of demand on traditional energy-supply systems. The
Solar Energy Research Institute (now the National Renewable Energy Laboratory)
played an instrumental role in Boulder's consciousness raising efforts.</P>

<P><BR>
<B>Creating a Workable Ordinance</B></P>

<P>The final design of Boulder's ordinance reflects many of the compromises
the city has struck with local builders. Of these, the most important is
the use of a hybrid area-wide regulatory model, which allows builders to
observe a uniform standard within neighborhoods rather than comply with
myriad requirements on adjoining properties. The wide area approach offers
a blanket assurance of solar access protection, complementing a permit system
that grants access in excess of area-wide protection through an application
and review process. The latter ensures the flexibility of the ordinance
to address site-specific needs.</P>

<P>Taken as a whole the ordinance protects and promotes solar access in
two ways:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>It assures existing buildings and systems continued access by limiting
  the amount of shade a new building may cast on adjoining property, and
  <BR>
  </LI>
  <LI>It maximizes passive solar access by specifying design features for
  new residential buildings and allows for present or future installation
  of solar technology.</LI>
</UL>

<P>To protect existing buildings' access to solar resources, Boulder's ordinance
invokes a solar fence concept. The ordinance mandates that any new construction
may not cast a shadow on the adjoining lot that is greater than the shadow
cast by a fence of a given height on the property line from 10 am to 2 pm
on the shortest day of the year. For purposes of solar-fence restrictions
the ordinance divides the city into three areas corresponding to typical
city zoning regions. Area I includes all single family neighborhoods, Area
II includes condominium and apartment buildings in medium- or high-density
neighborhoods, and Area III includes commercial and business areas. The
solar fence is four meters high in Area I and eight meters high in Area
II. The ordinance does not enforce a standard regulation in business and
commercial districts (Area III). Instead, individual building owners can
apply for protection from the shadows of adjoining construction. Decisions
are made on a case by case basis under the permit system.</P>

<P>The city of Boulder has identified solar, space and water heating as
the primary applications of solar energy in the area's homes and buildings.
To maximize the effectiveness of these applications the ordinance requires
that new developments be sited such that the longest axis of a building
roofline is within 30 degrees of true east-west, that roofs be flat or face
south, and that seven square meters of roof area per residential unit be
made available for solar collectors. To help property owners and developers
meet these design guidelines, the city's Planning Department - responsible
for implementation and administration of the ordinance - has outlined the
requirements in a brochure, and, with funding from the Solar Energy Research
Institute, built actual models illustrating them.</P>

<P>Administration of the ordinance has proven to be relatively simple. A
Planning Department employee conducts a review of all building permits.
This review includes a check for compliance with solar-access codes. To
ensure that administration does not place a financial burden on the city,
the department finances the processing of requests for commercial solar
access protection through application fees. These funds are used to defray
city costs and to hire outside consultants to examine the applications.</P>

<P><BR>
<B>Assessing Performance and Replicating Results</B></P>

<P>The novelty of Boulder's ordinance has been the greatest impediment to
its implementation. The determination of solar-fence impacts, the development
of educational models and the design of the permits were all first-time
events - Boulder had no template on which to design its ordinance. For those
reasons, the city emphasized training and education of its community.</P>

<P>As a result, the ordinance itself has been well accepted. Residents and
developers have accommodated the requirements with few complaints. City
officials have been unwilling, for instance, to grant exceptions to access
regulations simply because a solar-energy collector is not present or planned
striving to protect access even when it is not currently exploited. </P>

<P>Informal assessment of the solar-access ordinance has, however, revealed
some problems and raised some questions. Building orientation provisions,
for example have not always yielded the required results, suggesting a need,
in some cases, for performance based criteria. In addition there have been
very few applications for permits to secure additional access. The fact
that this provision is seldom used, however, may simply reflect that the
area-wide provisions of the ordinance offer sufficient protection in all
but a handful of cases.</P>

<P>Designing and implementing a solar-access ordinance has kept current
solar-energy options, such as solar water-heating, widely available to area
residents despite considerable growth in the Boulder community. It also
unfolds future options for the city, the flexibility of an ordinance designed
to change as technologies evolve will allow adaptation to new developments
in solar energy technology.</P>

<P>Boulder's solar-access ordinance was successfully designed and implemented
using techniques that are available to all communities. Boulder's success
may be credited to the fact that the program was conceived when public awareness
about energy consumption and conservation was high. Government tax credits
provided a substantial incentive to implement solar-energy initiatives.
When these tax credits were repealed, the incentive to experiment with solar
energy faded. Even in Boulder, people pursued energy-conservation measures
before switching to the use of solar energy. </P>

<P>Ultimately, Boulder's experience has been an exercise in community vision.
Its leaders saw a future in which sustainable energy systems would become
increasingly attractive to its residents. Although public demand for action
was modest, Boulder implemented a well-considered, flexible plan to promote
renewable energy long before a resource crisis forced this course.</P>

<P>Most important, Boulder's solar-access initiative demonstrates that planning
for the future need not be taxing to city finance or to individual residents.
The only true requirement for the initiative's replicability is that city
planners consider future resource needs and options - whether in solar access
or other important resource and land use issues - and prevent current activities
from foreclosing future options. Boulder has demonstrated that this can
be done simply and with little sacrifice.</TD>
<TD WIDTH="150" valign=top><P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>LOCATION</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1><BR>
The eastern foothills of the Rocky Mountains. </FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>SIZE</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1><BR>
58.4 square miles</FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>POPULATION</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1><BR>
225,339 </FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>PER CAPITA INCOME</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1><BR>
$17,359 </FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>FORM OF GOVERNMENT</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1><BR>
City Council/City Manager. </FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>CONTEXT:<BR>
</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1>Boulder has grown rapidly over the last quarter
century, expanding both its boundaries and its population. Its well educated
work force supports a growing scientific research and development industry
and a solid manufacturing base. Throughout its growth Boulder has striven
to maintain its environmental quality, promoting sustainability through
open space and wetland preservation; alternative transportation strategies;
renewable energy and energy conservation programs; and a host of other initiatives.
<!--pagebreak--><BR>
</FONT><HR><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=-1>ENVIRONMENTAL BENEFITS OF SOLAR DOMESTIC WATER HEATERS
(SDWH) IN BOULDER <BR>
</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=-1><BR>
Although solar domestic water heating currently makes up only a small part
of the Boulder region's water heating load, the positive impact on the environment
is significant. Assuming all of the SDWH systems presently installed were
working, solar energy would satisfy about 2 percent of the total water heating
load. The total effect on pollutant emissions would be as follows:</FONT></P>

<P><B><TT><FONT SIZE=-1>CO:Reduced by 828<BR>
lbs.</FONT></TT></B></P>

<P><B><TT><FONT SIZE=-1>NOx:Reduced by<BR>
1,030 lbs.<BR>
<BR>
CO2:Reduced by <BR>
2,400,000 lbs.<BR>
</FONT></TT></B></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1>The most optimistic scenario developed by a Colorado study
assumes that SDWH systems could provide about 4 percent of Boulder's total
water heating load. The net yearly impact on emissions would be:</FONT></P>

<P><B><TT><FONT SIZE=-1>CO:Reduced by <BR>
2,860 lbs.<BR>
<BR>
NOx:Reduced by <BR>
38,100 lbs. </FONT></TT></B></P>

<P><B><TT><FONT SIZE=-1>CO2:Reduced by<BR>
21,200,000 lbs.</FONT></TT></B></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1>In a twenty-year lifetime, the average SDWH system, when
offsetting electric water heating, will prevent an estimated 466 lbs. of
sulphur dioxide, 16 lbs. of carbon monoxide, 212 lbs. of nitrogen oxides,
and 108,000 lbs. of carbon dioxide from being released into the atmosphere.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1>According to guidelines published by the Nevada Public
Utilities Commission, preventing these pollutants from being emitted results
in savings to society of $2,280.<BR>
<BR>
<!--pagebreak--></FONT><HR><B><FONT SIZE=-1>BENEFITS OF SOLAR ACCESS</FONT></B><FONT
 SIZE=-1> </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1>Broad solar access protection, in addition to benefiting
individual landowners benefits the community as a whole. Solar access can
reduce energy costs and pollution; enhance market value, comfort and aesthetics;
and spark local economic activity and support jobs:</FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>Energy Savings </FONT></B></P>

<UL>
  <LI><FONT SIZE=-1>Properly orienting a home to the sun can reduce energy
  consumption by 10% or more. <BR>
  </FONT></LI>
  <LI><FONT SIZE=-1>A 60 ft2 solar hot water heating system in Boulder with
  a delivers 2950 kWh per year (a value of $177 at $.06 cents per kWh).</FONT></LI>
</UL>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Economic Activity/Jobs</FONT></B></P>

<UL>
  <LI><FONT SIZE=-1>Each $1.00 spent to acquire energy resources from outside
  a community generates only about $.33 of economic activity within the community.
  Every $1.00 spent on solar energy systems and services within the community
  produces about $1.67 of local economic activity. </FONT></LI>
</UL>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1>Environmental and Quality of Life Benefits</FONT></B></P>

<UL>
  <LI><I><FONT SIZE=-1>Pollutant emission reductions</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=-1>:
  solar energy reduces the amount of fuel consumed to produce electricity
  reducing regional air pollution<BR>
  </FONT></LI>
  <LI><I><FONT SIZE=-1>Comfort:</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=-1> pleasant, open,
  light filled interiors are aesthetically pleasing and enhance real estate
  value.<B> </B></FONT></LI>
</UL>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=-1><!--pagebreak-->It's a Fact...</FONT></B><HR></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1>Boulder is not the only community to realize the benefits
of protecting solar access. Research conducted in San Jose, California determined
that solar-access guidelines could save nearly 24 million kilowatt-hours
of electricity each year, reducing residential energy bills by $840,000
(in 1991 dollars) and eliminating nearly 5,500 tons of carbon dioxide emissions.
Numbers like these have convinced communities across the country to adopt
solar access guidelines.</FONT></P>

