<html><head>
<TITLE>The "Sustainable" Debate</TITLE>
</head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></a>

<A HREF="/articles/">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/articles.gif" ALT="= Articles on Sustainability ="></A>

<H2>The "Sustainable" Debate</H2>
<H4>Leaders look at health of area economy</H4>
<i>Nancy Nachman-Hunt</i><P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><P></CENTER>

<blockquote>
Well, maybe Boulder County is more than halfway to paradise. We've got jobs --lots of jobs, we've got record retail sales revenues, we've got open space, we've got an international reputation for being "the" American entrepreneurial hot spot.<P>

Beyond that, Newsweek Japan has dubbed the city of Boulder "an oasis of greenery."<P>

But, as all who live, work and run businesses here know, Boulder County also has serious growing pains. Witness the traffic jams at what county residents now can legitimately call rush hour. Witness the ever-increasing price of housing.<P>

As the growth/no-growth debate rages on the pages of local newspapers, in city council meetings and in offices all over the county, quality of life and economic growth seem to be at loggerheads. The November 1995 ballot issue that will ask voters whether to limit commercial growth in Boulder to 1 percent annually looms large in this scenario.<P>

Beginning Jan. 6, however, there may be a break in the log jam. That's the date 32 of the county's most high-profile business, government, education and cultural leaders plan to sit down together to begin to figure out how to create in Boulder County a sustainable community. Say, what?<P>

A sustainable community, according to Susan Boyd, director of CONCERN Inc., an environmental and education think tank, is one that, "in the broadest sense, resembles a living system in which all resources -- human, natural and economic -- are interdependent and draw strength from each other."<P>

The hope of all involved is that reframing the growth/no-growth debate into a discussion on how to create a sustainable community will have benefits countywide.<P>

It's not just another Boulder thing, says Gordon Pedrow, Longmont's city manager. "There is an entire county here which covers everything from the plains to the mountains, and a whole lot of people living here want to sustain the quality of life here.<P>

"Sustainability doesn't mean no growth. The words are not synonymous in any fashion. (Sustainability) talks about ensuring that the resources available now are available in the future. That isn't growth/no-growth."<P>

The definitions are admittedly vague. Cynthia Schmidt, deputy director of the Boulder-based Walter Orr Roberts Institute, says it's necessary to look at the notion of sustainability the same way people used to look at the notion of progress. "You can't have one set definition, it depends on the situation and the venue."

<a name = "toc">
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Definition">Definition</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Real">Real Estate Benefits</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Growth">Not Zero Growth</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Search">A Difficult Search</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Paradise">Halfway to Paradise (the numbers)</H3></a><P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<H3><A NAME="Definition">Definition</A></H3>

<blockquote>
It is the job of the 32 people meeting in January to begin the process of creating the definition of sustainability for Boulder County. Pedrow and Schmidt are among them. They and the others are members of an initiating committee that in September asked the Colorado Trust, a state philanthropy, for a grant to study sustainability.<P>

Committee members include the top city officials from Boulder, Longmont, Broomfield, Louisville, Lafayette and Superior; business leaders Charles Butcher, chairman of the Butcher Companies; Glenn Porzak, managing partner of Holme Roberts & Owen and board member of Norwest Banks; and Ken Hotard, senior vice president of government and community relations for the Boulder Area Board of Realtors; and representatives from the county's education, federal government, environmental and artistic communities.<P>

As initiating committee member Porzak says, "This is not the typical group you see showing up at a city council meeting. When I took a look at the list, I thought it was an honest attempt at getting a good cross-section of the community."<P>

Their proposal, "on behalf of the citizens of Boulder County," was accepted by the Colorado Trust on Nov. 30. The acceptance frees up about $62,500 in cash and in-kind contributions from the trust to begin the study.<P>

There are three factors working to ensure the ultimate success of this effort, according to initiating committee members.<P>

First, the study brings business, environmental and cultural leaders together. "Even if it doesn't result in one new idea, it brings a lot of people to the table that represent divergent views," says Hotard, whose real estate community constituents have a significant interest in whatever the outcome of this process is.<P>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<H3><A NAME="Real">Real</A> Estate Benefits</H3>

<blockquote>
Hotard says working toward some measure of sustainability is in the long-term benefit of the county's real estate marketplace. "If the quality of life in the county is upheld, if growth management is done well and fairly, the real estate community will benefit from it," he says.<P>

Second, the study will be a regional effort. Boulder City Manager Tim Honey says economists are increasingly identifying regions, rather than cities or states, as the true geographic economies in the United States. Honey also says the us-against-them quality of the historic dialog among communities in the county is fading.<P>

"Over the past couple of years, a really solid foundation has been laid for regional Cooperation," Honey says. He cites the county-wide open space policies and the approval of a county recycling facility by voters last November as evidence. "We are all coming to the realization in city government that there are questions on a municipal level that we can't really solve alone."<P>

Finally, committee members say this undertaking frames the quality of life issue in a larger context than simply growth/no-growth.<P>

"We want to look at how a community can maintain good quality of life and perhaps change some ways in which we are approaching growth issues. No new jobs and no new businesses is not an indicator of a healthy community," Schmidt says.<P>

While the notion of creating a sustainable community sounds comfortably Boulderlike, it has no roots here. In fact, the county is slightly behind other areas of the country in exploring this phenomenon.<P>

Cities and regions as diverse as Seattle and Chattanooga, Tenn.,  either have studied or are in the process of moving toward sustainable communities. At the national level, the White House has created a Presidents Council on Sustainable Development.<P>

The council's chairs are David Buzzelli, vice president and corporate director of the Dow Chemical Co., and Jonathan Lash, president of the World Resources Institute.<P>

Chattanooga plays host to the President's Council this month. The Walter Orr Roberts Foundation will host a roundtable on population growth at that meeting.<P>

In Seattle, Sustainable Seattle, a volunteer organization that has representation from the King County and Seattle city governments and business and environmental communities, has been working on sustainability issues for more than three years.<P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<H3>Not Zero <A NAME="Growth">Growth</A></H3>

<blockquote>
The Seattle group does not define sustainability as zero growth. "We are not spending a lot of time trying to define an absolute carrying capacity for the area. I'm not convinced a carrying capacity can be defined in a scientific way," says Steven Nicholas, senior environmental planner for the city of Seattle.<P>

Seattle and King County are trying to direct growth through a high-density, urban-village strategy, rather than to eliminate it, Nicholas says,
What Sustainable Seattle does do, however, is issue what it calls Indicators of Sustainable Community. The indicators are designed to show over time whether the King County area is moving toward or away from sustainability in several categories.<P>

Members of the sustainability study initiating committee here in Boulder County think the indicators may provide some direction for this region's upcoming discussions.<P>

"They are exactly the kind of thing we  hope  to achieve," Schmidt says.
There are 40 Sustainable Community indicators for the Seattle area. For brevity's sake, general categories will be used to describe them here. They include:<P>
<ul>
<LI>Under the environment umbrella -- biodiversity, air quality and the percentage of streets meeting "pedestrian-friendly criteria";<P>

<LI>Under the population and resources umbrella -- population, water consumption, recycling, traffic and energy consumption;<P>

<LI>Under the economy umbrella -- employment, wages, percentage of children living in poverty, housing affordability and health expenditures;<P>

<LI>Under the culture and society umbrella -- infant health, juvenile crime rates, community service participation, voting habits, literacy, public facility use and participation in the arts.<P>
</ul>

The Colorado Trust commissioned a set of similar indicators for the state of Colorado back in 1991. The result is known as the Colorado Index of Sustainable Economic Welfare, or ISEW, which is based on dollar figures and was created so that it could be compared to state gross domestic product growth. It puts dollar amounts on activities such as commuting, water and air pollution, loss of wetlands, net capital growth and income distribution spread.<P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<H3>A Difficult <A NAME="Search">Search</A></H3>

<blockquote>
From 1980 to 1990 the Colorado ISEW grew 24 percent. The state's gross state product, which measures productive capacity -- not the population's economic welfare -- grew at nearly the same rate.<P>

The problem with the ISEW, however, is that data on many of the categories used in the index are difficult. if not impossible, to find, say its creators, economists Michael Zimmerman and Vinson Snowberger.<P>

In fact, finding Colorado's gross state product measures before 1980 is equally difficult. The Statistical Abstract of the United States didn't begin including it in its listings until the 1980s, and Colorado has no state law that requires any state agency to calculate the state's GDP.<P>

Can any index really measure sustainability? "That's a good question," David Norcross, NIST director and initiating committee member, says. "Measuring things that are social is harder; you have to be careful about installing your own personal social agenda."<P>

If Boulder County creates its own measure of sustainability or sustainable economic welfare, it will no doubt contain some combination or permutations of the above. It also will draw from the baseline economy study currently being developed by the city of Boulder, the University of Colorado and the Boulder Development Commission. That study will be completed about the same time the sustainability study begins.<P>

The business community will be following the entire process with interest.
Attorney Porzak echoes the thinking of many when he says, "To say we are going to eliminate or severely restrict future economic development -- I don't think the consequences of that have been completely thought through."<P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<H3>Halfway to <A NAME="Paradise">Paradise</A></H3>

<blockquote>
Can Boulder County have economic vitality and high quality of life at the same time?  Here are what the numbers show: Wages are up and the county is technically at full employment. In 1993, the latest figures available, all county cities but Broomfield and Lafayette added businesses at a respectable clip. Consumer confidence is rising. Retail sales are up more than 12 percent from last year -- even before the holiday season numbers are tabulated.<P>

But the numbers also show that while the average paycheck has increased for county residents, the cost of living here has increased at an even greater rate.<P>

<h3>The Pluses</h3>
<blockquote>
