<TITLE>Outlook on Sustainable Enterprise</TITLE>
</head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></a>

<A HREF="/articles/">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/articles.gif" ALT="= Articles on Sustainability ="></A>

<H2>Outlook on Sustainable Enterprise</H2>
<i>Robert Steuteville and David Riggle</i><P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER><P>

<blockquote>
Throughout various commercial and industrial sectors, the shift to sustainability has been set into motion. The anecdotal evidence abounds -- factories institute pollution prevention measures, farms and vineyards shift to organic production, recycled content increases in consumer products -- but what does the big picture look like? How can it be measured?<P>

To bring these multisector activities into clearer focus, In Business undertook a review of sustainable enterprise. Data was gathered from sources which provide insight on how far the United States has traveled along the road to sustainability in a variety of business sectors. Put together, this "Outlook On Sustainable Enterprise" finds a movement that appears to be greater than the sum of its parts.<P>

Given the nature of the subject, many potential sources of data could have been included in this report. In Business chose a few that seemed relevant. The report should be considered a work in progress and we welcome feedback and suggestions for future updates.

<a name = "toc">
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Recycling">Recycling</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Food">Food and Agriculture</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Transportation">Transportation</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Alternative">Alternative Energy</H3></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Efficiency">Energy Efficiency</H3></a><P>
<H3><IMG SRC="/rsc/mball.gif" ALT=" * ">
<a href = "#Land">Land Use: Sprawl Versus Communities</H3></a><P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER><P>
<H3><A NAME="Recycling">Recycling</A></H3>

<blockquote>
Of all the sustainability indicators, no sector shows more dramatic changes in recent years than in the handling, recycling and reuse of materials that used to be considered waste. The scope and breadth of this change, which has touched upon U.S. households, businesses and industrial plants, point to a fundamental recognition that refuse represents resources. And, especially in industry, generation of waste itself now is viewed as a cost that should be eliminated.<P>

Nationwide, recycling of municipal solid waste (MSW) has increased from 10 percent in 1985 to 23 percent in 1994, according to "The State of Garbage In America," an annual survey conducted by BioCycle, Journal of Composting and Recycling. Part of that is due to municipal recycling programs, which have swept the country in recent years. Municipalities with curbside recycling have increased from about 1,000 in 1988 to more than 7,200 in 1994. Population served by these programs has reached 108 million, or 41 percent of U.S. households. Another sizable segment is served by multifamily recycling programs and dropoff sites.<P>

If popularity is any indicator, municipal recycling has been highly successful. Mandates of all kinds are generally frowned upon in the U.S., but 73 percent of residents favor laws requiring recycling, according to a recent Waste Management/Gallup poll. Those who live in communities where recycling is mandated favor it even more strongly (84 percent, compared to 66 percent in towns where recycling is not required).<P>

Recycling of organic materials, particularly yard trimmings and biosolids, has also made big gains. Facilities that compost yard trimmings rose from around 700 in 1988 to 3,200 in 1994. Operating biosolids composting  facilities nearly doubled, to 200, in that period.<P>

The commercial sector has played a significant role in increasing diversion. Spurred by mandates, environmental factors and/or reductions in disposal costs, businesses throughout the U.S. have begun or expanded recycling programs. In l992, 23 million tons of MSW were recycled by businesses, considerably more than the amount recycled by the nation as a  whole in 1985 (16.4 million tons).<P>

Pollution prevention has become standard practice at industrial plants, as companies realize that eliminating toxic waste saves money as well as reduces liability. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's Toxic Release Inventory of 300 dangerous chemicals released into the environment has decreased steadily to 2.8 billion pounds in
1993, from four billion pounds in 1988.<P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="Food">Food</A> and Agriculture</H3>

<blockquote>
While the number of farmers who use organic practices has remained fairly stable in the last 15 years -- at about 10,000 to 12,000, according to the Organic Farming Research Foundation (OFRF) in Santa Cruz, California -- the average size of each farm has risen substantially. "Back in 1980, there were a lot of 10 to 20 acre organic farms; now you see 160 and 300 and 3,000 acre operations," says Bob Scowcroft, executive director of the OFRF.<P>

Although  currently there are no national figures for the number of acres cultivated with organic techniques, considerable data demonstrates that the industry is growing. One group, the California Certified Organic Farmers, had 244 members in 1988, managing 16,755 certified acres. Since then, the number of members has grown to 528, but more significantly, the total acreage has risen to 50,409. The average farm size therefore increased by 39 percent, from 69 to 95 acres.<P>

One organic crop with symbolic value as an indicator of sustainability is cotton, due to its 45 year history of profound dependence on chemical pesticides and fertilizers. By some estimates almost twice as many pesticides are applied to cotton -- 40 million pounds per year -- than to all other crops combined. Although still only a small percentage of the total amount of cotton is grown in the U.S., the progress organic cotton has made in a relatively short time is dramatic. According to the National Cotton Council, the estimated number of acres planted in cotton using organic methods was 10,600 acres in 1994, compared to only 150 acres in 1990. Including "transitional" or "pending" acreage -- which generally becomes fully certified organic after a three-year chemical free hiatus -- the total for both in 1994 was around 33,000 acres. That's more than 25 times the total certified and pending organic cotton acreage in 1990.<P>

A project sponsored by the U.S. Department of Agriculture is designed to determine the number of organically farmed acres, but figures are not yet available. Julie Aaron Dunn, who is conducting the survey, attributed the overall growth trend to a maturation of the industry. "The bigger growers are getting into it, and as farmers improve their organic techniques they expand the acreage," Dunn says. One factor may be the growth in the market for organic products, which rose from $1 billion nationwide in 1990 to $2.3 billion in 1994, according to New Hope Communications, which tracks natural and organic food markets.<P>

The movement toward sustainability in agriculture extends into conventional farming -- which has been influenced by the organic research, according to Rob Myers, director of the USDA's sustainable agriculture program. "Organic producers have had to struggle the most to find ways of doing things without chemical fertilizers and pesticides. That in turn has benefited the people who do not want to become organic, but want to reduce their nitrogen or pesticide use."<P>

Government policies in the last decade have played a part in promoting sustainability. Since the 1985 Farm Bill, the Natural Resources Conservation Service (NRCS) has had measurable success in reducing soil erosion. In particular, Myers says, 36 million acres of highly erodible land (steeply sloped, or susceptible to strong winds) has been taken out of production. Practices have been changed on up to 100 million more acres, reducing the estimated erosion on these lands to 5.8 tons/acre/year in  1994,  from  16.2 tons/acre/year in 1985, according to the NRCS.<P>

Farmers have cut their use of nitrogen fertilizer, mainly due to greater research and awareness of how it can be reduced without sacrificing yields. "That does have a positive  effect on sustainability," Myers says. Federal support of sustainable agriculture research and education has grown steadily since 1987, when it was first funded at $4 million. In the current budget, the funding is $12 million -- although under this budget cutting climate, the future is uncertain.<P>

Another signpost pointing towards sustainability can be seen in the growth of Community Supported Agriculture (CSA). This partnership between local food producers and buyers involves a group of consumers contracting with a farmer for fresh fruits and vegetables throughout the growing season. The consumers pay up front for a share of the harvest which provides income for the farmer. The CSA keeps food dollars in the local economy and points to the possibilities of more regional agriculture production, while promoting a sense of community among shareholders.         <P>

Although variations have been  functioning in Europe and Japan for 25  years or more, CSAs were first introduced to the U.S. in 1985.  Robyn Van En signed up the first families for her Indian Line Farm CSA in Great     Barrington, Massachusetts, in 1986. A  nonprofit organization she helped form to promote the concept -- Community Supported Agriculture of North  America (CSANA) -- estimates there are 500 CSA operations in the U.S. and Canada with 50 more to be added this year. If they follow the CSA model, the project will use sustainable agriculture of some kind, usually organic or biodynamic techniques. "None of the ones we're counting still use chemicals or exploitive methods," she says. "This is win-win agriculture."<P>

Melody Newcombe, publishing editor of The Harvest Times, a newsletter
for "farmers and consumers linked through community  supported agriculture," also has run her own CSA. "When I first started thinking about doing the newsletter in
1990 there probably were only around 65 operating
CSAs in North America," she says. "They tend to stop and start for a variety of reasons, so it's difficult to keep track from year to year, but I know of at least
400 active CSAs right now in the U.S. and Canada."<P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="Transportation">Transportation</A></H3>

<blockquote>
The number of motor vehicles on the road in the U.S. keeps going up (195 million in 1994, compared to 130 million in 1974), but there are some positive trends in the industry that bode well for sustainability. Although still a tiny niche, the electric vehicle industry is showing growth. A recent study by the Electric Vehicle Association of the Americas (EVAA) estimates that there are currently between 2,078 and 2,369 electric cars operating in the U.S., a five-fold increase from five years ago. "We're still in the prototype and demonstration phase," says Athena Fristoe of EVAA. "We have not reached the point of mass market commercial production."<P>

More important than the current numbers, however, is the development of technology which holds the promise to lower the costs and improve range and efficiency of electric vehicles, Fristoe adds. The EVAA is predicting a more rapid commercialization of electric vehicles, driven by low or zero emission mandates in states like California, New York and Massachusetts. Operating vehicles could total 70,000 by 1998, according to the study. "We think the industry can gear up to meet any requirements," Fristoe says.<P>

One key to expanding the market for electric vehicles is range. At the American Tour de Sol, the largest U.S. electric car road race, the records are broken every year. The most recent is 238 miles, set by Solectria Corp. of Wilmington, Massachusetts, according to Nancy Hazard, the director of the Northeast Sustainable Energy Association (NSEA), which sponsors the event. As recently as 1989, the Tour de Sol record was 35 miles. A survey by Ford Motor Company led the automaker to conclude that if an electric car can be mass produced at a reasonable cost with a 100 to 125 mile range, it would have significant market appeal. "It's very encouraging to hear that from Ford, because 100 to 125 miles is a reachable goal," says Hazard. In addition to electric cars, alternative vehicle technologies being developed with potential sustainability benefits include hydrogen power and fuel cells. Natural gas technology (which holds particular promise for buses and fleet vehicles), still relies on a fossil fuel, but is less polluting. Some look to natural gas as an interim step while zero emission vehicles are in development.<P>

An interesting parallel trend involves automotive energy efficiency. The average passenger car averaged nearly 22 miles/gallon (mpg) in 1993, up from 13 mpg in 1973. That increase, which has saved huge amounts of fuel in the U.S., is nothing compared to the potential, according to some experts. Amory Lovins, who predicted the "negawatt"  efficiency movement in the power industry, now believes that "hypercars" will be the wave of the future. Hypercars are ultralight autos that, in theory, could achieve l00 mpg, and perhaps several times that level of efficiency, without sacrificing performance or safety. They are based on emerging technologies in composite materials, combined with the development of hybrid electric/gasoline engines.<P>
</blockquote>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="Alternative">Alternative</A> Energy</H3>

<blockquote>
There is bad news and good news on the alternative energy front in the U.S. The figures from the Department of Energy (DOE) in recent years illustrate this reality: renewable energy is still a small part of U.S. energy generation, and that is not likely to change in the foreseeable future. With the exception of off-grid (and therefore hard to measure) solar panel installations, and some utility scale wind power expansions in Texas and the northern plains states, there has been little overall increase in U.S. renewable capacity. The DOE shows a very small rise in combined solar and wind energy generation in the U.S. during the years 1990 through 1993 (from 0.09 quadrillion Btu to 0.10 quadrillion Btu). To give a sense of perspective, that amounts to about 0.001 percent of U.S. energy consumption.<P>

The good news is that there is much greater development of renewables abroad, and companies located in the U.S. are contributing to that change. One dramatic example is photovoltaic cell and module shipments on the part of U.S. firms, which according to the Department of Energy (DOE), reached 21 megawatts of capacity in 1993. That figure has risen steadily since 1985, when it was less than six megawatts. About 30 percent of all photovoltaic cells and modules are made in the U.S. (although Siemens, the largest U.S. producer, is headquartered in Germany).<P>

Most of the increase appears to be in the export market, particularly shipments to developing countries like Brazil, Argentina, China and Singapore. The potential markets are enormous, according to Larry Sherwood of the American Solar Energy Society. Households without electricity amount to 20 percent of the total in Brazil, and 50 percent in China, he says. India has 72,000 villages without power. "Having a light bulb and a television is becoming increasingly important to people around the world. That's why the future is bright for this technology," Sherwood says. Despite the relatively high cost for solar panels, it is competitive when serving remote locations where there are no power lines. When available capital is low, photovoltaics may be the only option.<P>

As industry gears up to
serve international markets, it could hasten the day when it is cost-effective for utility applications in the U.S., Sherwood adds. That day is a long way off, however. Currently, photovoltaics are cost-effective only for niche U.S. markets -- security lighting, billboards, remote households -- locations where laying down power lines would be too expensive, he says. The U.S. regulatory system is moving away from subsidizing renewable energy sources, given the trend toward utility market competition, says Nick Lenssen of the Worldwatch Institute. But that is not the case overseas. "Most governments support renewable energy. We are the exception these days," he says. Industrialized countries like Germany, Switzerland, Canada and Japan are purchasing U.S. made solar panels, and in some cases, sales are helped by the declining value of the dollar.<P>

A similar trend is taking place in wind power. As mentioned above, there is some expansion of U.S. wind power capacity, and the DOE is expecting it to grow by 13 percent annually through the year 2000. Wind farms can generate electricity for as low as five cents/kilowatt hour in some parts of the country, which makes it nearly competitive with gas turbines, currently the lowest cost source of new energy. But like solar, wind is growing faster in other countries, and U.S. companies are sharing in that market. Wind is making significant strides' in Germany, where 300 megawatts of new capacity were installed in 1994, and also in India and China.<P>

Gas turbines, although not renewable, represent a positive step in sustainability, Lenssen adds. They are less polluting and far more efficient than coal or petroleum plants. A new General Electric gas turbine technology, the H-series, operates at about 60 percent efficiency, nearly double that of the average coal power plant, he explains.  Gas turbines, because they require smaller capital expenditures and represent the lowest cost technology, will get a boost from the market oriented regulatory changes that are taking place in the U.S.<P>
</blockquote>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3>Energy <A NAME="Efficiency">Efficiency</A></H3>

<blockquote>
While alternative fuel technologies develop, energy efficiency at least slows down the rate of increase in U.S. consumption of fossil fuels. Take refrigerators, for example. In 1993, the average new model used 660 kilowatt hours/year, compared to 1,726 kilowatt hours/year in 1972, according to the Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers (AHAM). That represents a decrease of nearly two-thirds in energy use, while the average refrigerator actually grew in size.<P>

Substantial efficiency gains also have been made in lighting, industrial motors, heating, transportation and other sectors of the economy. As a result, energy use/unit of gross domestic product in the U.S. has dropped by 30 percent since 1973, which has cut the rate of increase in energy demand. Total U.S. energy use has grown during that period by about 15 percent.<P>

One driving force behind efficiency has been demand side management (DSM) programs on the part of utilities, which work on the theory that it is profitable to pay consumers to cut power use. DSM has grown rapidly in recent years. Expenditures have risen to an estimated $3 billion in 1994 from $873 million in 1989, according to the DOE. During that time, annual energy savings from DSM programs have risen to an estimated 53 million kilowatt hours, from 16 million kilowatt hours. The future of DSM is uncertain, as regulatory changes open utilities up to market competition. Experts differ as to whether DSM will be helped or hurt by the rule changes, according to Larry Prete, of the DOE's Energy Information Administration." This is a bad time to extrapolate into the future, because the power industry will change quite markedly in the next few years."<P>

Owen Bailey, spokesman for the Rocky Mountain Institute in Snowmass, Colorado, says that the future for energy efficiency is very bright, regardless of the regulatory climate. In the computer industry (which represents one of the biggest increases in electricity demand in recent years), energy efficient models have been developed for personal computers, printers and other accessories, says Bailey. "As people update their computer equipment we should eventually see drops in demand in this sector." Industrial motors, which use up to 50 percent of the electric power in the U.S., could cost effectively be replaced with models that are twice as efficient, he adds. "As more energy efficient technologies become available, the costs go down," Bailey says. "That is unlike fossil fuel supplies, which are slowly dwindling. Those costs should eventually be driven up."<P>
</blockquote>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="Land">Land</A> Use: Sprawl Versus Communities</H3>

<blockquote>
Suburban sprawl has dominated the U.S. landscape for the last 50 years, gobbling up farmland with cookie-cutter housing developments, shopping centers, malls and, lately, "big box" department stores. While national figures on sprawl are hard to come by, data has been gathered on a regional basis. In the Chicago region, developed land increased at least 40 percent between 1970 and 1990, while population increased only four percent, according to the Northeastern Illinois Planning Commission.  Moreover, growth patterns in northeastern Illinois show that the greatest increases were on the outskirts of the metropolitan region, while the city and inner suburbs lost residents or remained stable. These general trends hold true in metropolitan regions throughout the U.S.<P>

For most of the last half century, there has been no alternative to sprawl. But in the last decade, a counter movement has begun to take hold to build communities, rather than developments. This is taking two forms, called "new urbanism" and  "eco-villages." Both include tightly clustered development, public open space, pedestrian oriented design, and mixed commercial and residential properties. "You need to have the mixture of business and residential in the same area so people don't have to drive as often," says Brian Drewes, with the Eco-Village in Ithaca, a development of 30 homes that is planned to begin construction in the summer of 1995 in New York State. Eco-villages, of which there are about a half dozen planned in the U.S., focus more directly on environmental technologies, i.e. alternative energy, and the concept of cohousing, a cooperative living philosophy which began in Denmark 20 years ago.<P>

The new urbanism (also called neotraditional or transit oriented development) is a larger phenomenon, with an estimated 125 projects nationwide, according to Peter Kale, author of The New Urbanism: Toward an Architecture of Community. Most are in the planning stages, but at least a dozen are under construction (it is still a fraction of one percent of the total construction industry). Nevertheless, it is fair to say that no embryonic development concept has received so much attention  --  Newsweek recently published a major story on the subject, for example,  and so has just   about every major newspaper and news magazine in recent years. "On the one hand, you have continued sprawl and the tendency toward big box retail stores," Katz says.  "But there  is  also  tremendous interest in   new types of development. What you have is two freight trains going in opposite directions, and only time will tell whether they are on a collision course."<P>

The trend toward designing for community, and more prudent use of land resources, is being driven by dissatisfaction with suburbia, Katz says. Nevertheless, there are significant challenges ahead for forward thinking developers, including regulatory barriers, demonstration of market viability and inertia in the housing industry. The first hurdle may be the largest: zoning codes adopted nation-wide in the last 50 years explicitly forbid dense, mixed-use, pedestrian oriented development.  Although there are a handful of locations where it is permitted and  even  encouraged, in most municipalities new urbanism or eco-villages require zoning   variances, which can take months or years for approval.  Proving market viability  and overcoming inertia are related issues.  Banks and builders are reluctant to become involved with an unproven concept.  "It's the chicken and egg syndrome," Katz says. "The problem is getting the market validation when the option is generally not available in the marketplace." If the developments that are coming on line prove to be financially successful, however, this equation may change.<P>
</blockquote>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
