<!--**head**-->
</P>
<H2>Taming Urban Sprawl: Healthy Cities and Towns</H2>  
<P><I>Northwest Report January 1996</I>
</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></P>
<P>

</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><CENTER>__________________________________________________________________</CENTER>
<P><B><I>Urban sprawl is the legacy of North America's neglect of
environmental  consequences.  That legacy has spawned congestion, air pollution,
long commutes, and  a host of other ills.  Mark Roseland describes what cities
and towns can do to break that  pattern and enhance environmental stability,
economic efficiency, and  social equity -  which will bring not only local but
also global benefits.  Roseland is a planner who  teaches in the community
economic development program at Simon Fraser University in  Vancouver, British
Columbia.  This article is based on his book, <B>Toward  Sustainable
Communities:  A</B> <B>Resource Book for Municipal and Local  Governments</B>,
which is available from the National Round Table on the  Environment and the
Economy, 1 Nicholas Street, Suite 1500, Ottawa, Ontario, Canada  K1N 7B7; phone:
 (613)992-7189; fax:  (613)992-7385.</I></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER>________________________________________________________________</CENTER>
<P>By the year 2000, nearly half of the world's people will live in urban
areas.  Most North  American cities were built on technologies that emphasized
economic goals and assumed  that abundant supplies of cheap energy would always
be available.  In the process,  environmental consequences were neglected or
ignored.  Many communities grew rapidly  and inefficiently.  Cheap energy made
it possible to increase the geographic areas from  which cities could draw their
raw materials, so they became dependent on extended  distribution systems.  The
notion of cheap, abundant energy also affected building  construction,
dependence on the automobile, increased separation between the workplace  and
home, and the design and livability of our cities.  </P>
<P>
The legacy of our pattern of fossil fuel consumption is urban sprawl.  A belief
in  entitlement to cheap fuel and unrestricted use of vehicles, whatever the
social and  environmental costs, pervades our developed society.  Per capita
gasoline consumption in  the United States and many Canadian cities is now more
than four times that of European  cities and ten times that of Asian cities such
as Tokyo, Hong Kong, and Singapore.  The  biggest factor accounting for these
differences in energy use appears to be the efficiency  and compactness of land
use patterns.</P>
<P>
Other local and regional consequences of sprawl - such as congestion, air
pollution, the  imbalance between job and housing locations, and longer
commuting times - are now  widely acknowledged.  Until recently, however, few
researchers recognized that the land  use patterns of North American cities also
have serious global ecological ramifications.   According to recent research at
the International Institute for  Applied Systems Analysis, if  North American
cities modeled future development on cites like Amsterdam, future carbon 
dioxide emissions here would only be half as much as current gloomy projections
now  indicate.  Similar arguments could be made regarding water, energy, and
waste  disposal.</P>
<P>
The postwar pattern of Western urban development is not only ecologically 
unconscionable, it is also economically inefficient and socially inequitable. 
The physical  infrastructure costs of pipelines, utilities, poles, roads, and so
on are considerably more  expensive than they need to be, especially since many
of the costs are borne by local  taxpayers.  The social costs are high as well -
in a society in which an automobile is a  virtual necessity, the old, the young,
the poor, and the disabled are automatically  marginalized.</P>
<P>
In contrast, the concept of sustainable communities implies that the use of
energy and  materials is in balance with such processes as photosynthesis and
waste assimilation.   Achieving balance requires increasing community and
regional self-reliance to reduce  dependency on imports.  The benefits are
reduced energy budgets, reduced material  consumption, and a smaller, more
compact urban pattern interspersed with productive  areas for collecting energy,
growing crops, and recycling wastes.</P>
<P>
Cities with less dependence on the automobile are more centralized, have more
intense  land use (more people and jobs per unit area), are more oriented to
non-auto travel modes  (walking, bicycling, public transit), and place more
restraints on high-speed traffic.  This  suggests a new approach to
transportation and land use planning in North America.  </P>
<P>
This new approach is illustrated by a San Jose, California, study in which
development  pressures with and without a greenbelt were compared.  Without the
greenbelt, 13,000  exurban homes would be developed that, compared to an
equivalent number of units  downtown and along the transit corridor, would
require at least an additional 200,000  miles of auto commuting, an extra 3
million gallons of water, and 40 percent more energy  for heating and cooling
every day.</P>
<P>
<B>THINKING LONG-TERM, ACTING NOW</B></P>
<P>
Local environmentalists, citizen activists, and, increasingly, municipal
officials are  beginning to recognize that the way our urban areas are developed
will largely determine  our success or failure in overcoming environmental
challenges and achieving sustainable  development.  From a sustainable community
perspective, the amount of growth is less  important than the pattern of growth
in determining the level of environmental impact and  the efficiency of resource
use.</P>
<P>
In this context of growing concern over global environmental problems, citizen 
organizations and municipal officials all across North America are developing
creative  solutions to complex sustainable development challenges.  Although
local governments are  not the only agencies charged with community planning and
development, they are the only  locally elected, representative, and accountable
bodies responsible for community  decision-making.  This makes them critical
players in the movement toward sustainable  communities.</P>
<P>
Historically, most local governments have been hesitant to act, even in the face
of  overwhelming evidence of global environmental decline.  Resources at the
local  government level are often scarce, but the real problem seems to be one
of perception.   Both citizens and government officials have been inhibited by a
narrow definition of the  proper role of local government, and the result has
been a lack of mobilization to address  global problems that are largely rooted
in local day-to-day activities.  As the following  examples attest, this
situation is beginning to change dramatically.  Local communities are 
developing many concrete changes in economic, political, and social behavior
and, in the  process, are providing models for nationwide policies and programs.</P>
<P>
<B>Transportation Planning and Traffic Management</B></P>
<P>
Both local and global air quality problems demonstrate that transportation
planning and  traffic management initiatives are critical for sustainable urban
development.  These  initiatives are usually motivated by goals to, for example,
reduce the number of automobile  trips, increase opportunities for alternative
forms of transportation, and reduce the use of  gasoline and diesel fuel in
conventional autos, buses, and trucks.  Examples include:</P>
<P>
  Trip reduction by-laws to reduce single-occupant vehicle trips and increase
carpooling  (at least 37 California cities and towns)</P>
<P>
  Road pricing, such as tolls, relating to time of day or emissions (Singapore,
Hong  Kong, and Oslo)</P>
<P>
  Traffic-calming measures to slow traffic and reclaim streets for pedestrians
and  cyclists (many cities in Germany and The Netherlands)</P>
<P>
  Free or inexpensive transit in the downtown core (Portland, Oregon)</P>
<P>
  Programs to shift the emphasis of bicycle use from recreation to
transportation (Palo  Alto and Davis, California; Bordeaux, France)</P>
<P>
<B>Land Use Planning and Housing</B></P>
<P>
Land use planning and housing initiatives are also critical elements in
sustainable urban  development.  They are often based on the recognition that
transportation planning and  traffic management initiatives will eventually be
thwarted or simply overwhelmed by  growth unless accompanied by long-term
efforts to reduce the need for travel.  Examples  include:</P>
<P>
  Planning to make &quot;access by proximity rather than access by
transportation&quot; a central  focus of urban planning (Vancouver, British
Columbia)</P>
<P>
  Residential intensification in existing buildings or on previously developed,
serviced  land (Kingston, St. Catherines, and Metro Toronto, Ontario, Canada)</P>
<P>
  Community land trusts to remove land from the speculative market and hold it
for the  benefit of a community and its residents (Philadelphia, Atlanta, and
Providence)</P>
<P>
<B>Energy Conservation and Efficiency</B></P>
<P>
Reducing resource consumption requires initiatives in energy conservation and
efficiency,  both within local government and throughout the municipality, such
as:</P>
<P>
  Energy-efficient targets designed to increase energy efficiency in all sectors
of the city  (Portland, Oregon)</P>
<P>
  Municipal energy conservation campaigns (Osage, Iowa)</P>
<P>
  Energy-conservation retrofit ordinances that require all existing commercial
and/or  residential buildings to be brought up to an energy conservation
standard at the time of  sale (San Francisco)</P>
<P>
<B>Waste Reduction and Recycling</B></P>
<P>
Reducing resource consumption also requires initiatives in waste reduction and
recycling,  such as:</P>
<P>
  Packaging restrictions to encourage a recyclable and compostable waste stream 
(Minneapolis)</P>
<P>
  Restrictions on the use of polystyrene plastic foam to prevent one-time use of
these  containers by restaurants and retail food vendors (Portland, Oregon;
Berkeley)</P>
<P>
  Constructed wetlands (engineered marshes) to treat sewage (Arcata, California)</P>
<P>
  Solar aquatics waste-treatment facilities to mimic natural marshes in a
greenhouse for  treating sewage and septage at the neighborhood level
(Providence, Rhode Island)</P>
<P>
  Water offset requirements on new projects, requiring developers to replace old
toilets  in existing buildings with low-flow models, to free up enough water to
build (Santa  Barbara, San Luis Obispo, and Santa Monica, California)</P>
<P>
<B>Community Economic Development</B></P>
<P>
A sustainable community economy emphasizes sustainable employment and economic 
demand management (EDM).  Sustainable employment includes turning wastes into 
resources (for example, recycling); improving efficiency in energy and materials
use;  shifting reliance to renewable energy sources; increasing community
self-reliance (for  example, in food and energy production); and practicing
sustainable management of natural  resources (such as community forestry).  EDM
shifts the economic development emphasis  from the traditional concern with
increasing growth to a new focus:  reducing social  dependence on economic
growth.  Examples of sustainable community economic  development include:</P>
<P>
  Sustainable employment plans to create jobs, spur private spending, and reduce
 pollution through public investment in energy conservation and audits (San
Jose,  California)</P>
<P>
  New product development to encourage manufacturers to develop environmentally 
friendly products through municipal research and development assistance
(Gothenberg,  Sweden)</P>
<P>
  Increasing affordable housing supplies through zoning codes that promote a
variety of  housing types, including smaller and multifamily homes (Portland,
Oregon)</P>
<P>
  Experimenting with local self-reliance by establishing closed-loop,
self-sustaining  economic networks (St. Paul, Minnesota)</P>
<P>
  Community-supported agriculture to preserve farmland and help farmers while
making  fresh fruits and vegetables available in city neighborhoods (New York
City)</P>
<P>
  Encouraging local-ownership development projects with a revolving loan fund to
 encourage employee-owned businesses, which are considered both more stable over
 the long term and more likely to hire, train, and promote local residents
(Burlington,  Vermont)</P>
<P>
<B>Community Livability</B></P>
<P>
Initiatives to improve community livability demonstrate that efforts to fulfill
human needs,  improve social equity, and provide for social self-determination
must be pursued in  concert with initiatives to maintain ecological integrity. 
Examples include:</P>
<P>
  Partnerships between government and the nonprofit sector (for example, linkage
 programs) to help meet community needs (Boston and San Francisco)</P>
<P>
  Integrated environmental and social policy initiatives, such as a prison
greenhouse  aquaculture/hydroponics program that provides food for the prison
and the community  while training inmates for future employment (Bridgewater,
Massachusetts)</P>
<P>
  Healthy community projects to create public policy at the community level
(Rouyn- Noranda, Quebec; Seattle)</P>
<P>
<B>Sustainable Administration</B></P>
<P>
The road to sustainable development is potholed with failed efforts to
incorporate the  environment into everyday social and economic decision-making. 
In some cases, local  governments have even passed the same environmental
legislation twice in 10 years - a  sure sign that the intended measures were not
implemented the first time!  Conventional  wisdom considers the environment as
an administrative problem, to be solved by better  management; this generally
means cutting the environment into bite-sized pieces for its  protection.  This
approach seems increasingly inadequate for dealing effectively and 
comprehensively with environmental complexities.  Evidently administration, not
the  environment, is the real problem.  The alternative to conventional urban
administration is  an emerging form of what has been called &quot;environmental
administration.&quot; It can be  characterized as noncompartmentalized, open,
decentralized, antitechnocratic, and flexible.   Examples of some current
attempts to develop sustainable forms of administration  include:</P>
<P>
  Environmental commitments and legislation to reduce the threat of atmospheric
change  (Toronto and Vancouver)</P>
<P>
  Investment and purchasing or procurement policies that favor environmentally
sound  business practices or encourage or create markets for recycled materials
(New York  City and Toronto)</P>
<P>
  Employment of eco-counselors, who review the environmental impact of all
municipal  practices and recommend environmentally sound practices to various
government  departments (cities in a t least 10 European countries)</P>
<P>
  Community roundtables to bring diverse perspectives together to work on
sustainable  development (many Canadian cities, including Peterborough)</P>
<P>
  Networking and cooperative research as provided through such organizations as
the  International Council for Local Environmental Initiatives</P>
<P>
<B>MAKING IT HAPPEN</B></P>
<P>
The movement toward sustainable communities is guided by community leaders who
have  participated in initiatives like those outlined above.  Sustainable
communities of the future  are being constructed by social invention today. 
Taken together, the initiatives noted here  begin to indicate a strategy for
achieving a globally conscious culture of sustainability in  our cities.  They
also offer some practical suggestions on how to design effective  sustainable
community development policies.  Any sustainable development policy  framework
should recognize the following factors:</P>
<P>
<B>Sustainable development requires sustainable communities.</B>  Despite the 
concentration of population in urban areas, most city and local governments lack
the  regulatory and financial authority required to contribute effectively to
sustainable urban  development.  Other levels of government must provide
resources and support for the  financing, management, and policymaking authority
necessary for local governments to  achieve sustainable development in their
communities.</P>
<P>
<B>Sustainability can mean less as well as more.</B>  As long as sustainable 
development is conceived merely as environmental protection, it will be
understood as an  &quot;added&quot; cost to be &quot;traded&quot; against.  Once
sustainable development is conceived as doing  development differently, such
trade-offs become less critical; instead, the new focus is on  finding ways to
cease much of what we are doing and use the resources thus freed for  socially
and ecologically sustainable activities.</P>
<P>
<B>Social equity is essential.</B>  Inequities undermine sustainable
development, making  it essential to consider the distributive effects of
actions intended to advance sustainable  development.  For example, growth
management ordinances in many western U.S. cities  were enacted to safeguard the
environment and protect the quality of community life.  The  unintended result
has been to tighten local housing supplies, thereby driving up prices and 
causing serious problems for low- and moderate-income households.  By economic 
necessity, these households have leapfrogged across preserved open space to less
 expensive communities or undeveloped areas in the region.  The resulting longer
 commutes, increased traffic congestion, and worsening air pollution threaten
the very  quality of life that the control measure were intended to preserve.</P>
<P>
<B>Public participation is itself a sustainable development strategy.</B>  To a
 considerable extent, the environmental crisis is a crisis in creativity.  By
soliciting the bare  minimum of public input, rather than actively seeking
community participation at all levels,  local and national decision-makers have
failed to tap the well of human ingenuity.  They  have failed to recognize that
only from this source can we find ways to meet the myriad  challenges of
redeveloping our communities for sustainability.  Effective, acceptable local 
solutions require local decisions, which in turn require the extensive knowledge
and  participation of the people most affected by those decisions.</P>
<P>
Sustainable development requires that we develop our communities to be
sustainable in  global ecological terms.  This strategy can be effective not
only in preventing a host of  environmental and related social disasters, but
also in creating healthy cities and towns that  will be more pleasant and
satisfying for their residents than those we live in today.</P>
<P>
Sustainable cities and towns will emphasize the efficient use of urban space,
reduce  consumption of material and energy resources, and encourage long-term
social and  ecological health.  They will be cleaner, healthier, and less
expensive than our present-day  communities; they will have greater
accessibility and cohesion; and they will be more self- reliant in energy, food
supplies, and economic security.  Sustainable communities will not,  therefore,
merely sustain the quality of our lives - they will improve it.</P> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>  
<P>
  
<!--**foot**--></P>
