<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Entrepreneurs and Ecosystems: Building Sustainable Economies</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<P><A HREF="/"><IMG
ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A> 
<A HREF="/articles/"><IMG
ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/bugs/articles.gif" ALT="= Articles on Sustainability ="></A>
<BR CLEAR="all"><BR> 
<!--**head**-->
</P>
<H2>Entrepreneurs and Ecosystems: Building Sustainable Economies</H2>  
<P><I>Northwest Report January 1996</I>
</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>

</P>
<CENTER>_________________________________________________________________________________________</CENTER>
<P><I>The fortunes of local economies, communities, and ecosystems go hand in
hand.  The  goal of conservation-based development, explain Bettina von Hagen
and Erin Kellogg,  is to help entrepreneurs succeed in environmentally and
socially sound economic  enterprises, creating a &quot;win-win-win&quot;
situation for business, communities, and the  environment.  Von Hagen is
director of ecological economics for Ecotrust, a Portland- based conservation
organization, a former vice president at First Interstate Bank in  Portland, and
a Ph.D. student and lecturer in conservation-based development at  Portland
State University.  Kellogg is director of policy for Ecotrust and has worked on 
environmental policy for both private and government organizations.</I></P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER>_____________________________________________________________________________________</CENTER>
<P>As our planet's water quality has deteriorated, fish stocks have declined,
and soil  contamination has increased, people have begun to recognize that
economic development  that does not consider the health of underlying ecosystems
is fundamentally flawed - as is  development that neglects community vitality. 
Out of this recognition - that development  and conservation are not opposed,
but are in fact inseparable and mutually reliant - has  come the concept of
sustainable development.</P>
<P>
Paralleling this trend is a growing movement for environmental justice, a
response to  current inequities in environmental protection and development. 
Proposed siting of  environmentally troublesome facilities such as manufacturing
complexes, hazardous waste  sites, or incinerators trigger not-in-my-backyard
(NIMBY) reactions in surrounding  neighborhoods.  As a result, such facilities
often end up in disadvantaged neighborhoods,  which lack the resources and
political connections to join the &quot;NIMBY&quot; fight.  These  disadvantaged
neighborhoods, which are least able to afford mitigation measures, have 
increasingly borne the costs of economic growth.</P>
<P>
The trends toward sustainable development and environmental justice both reflect
a crucial  weakness in the conservation and environmental movements to date -
their failure to  incorporate the needs of people and communities, particularly
disadvantaged communities.   Failing to address those needs also means failing
to recognize and to draw on the immense  energy and creativity of local people
to solve environmental problems.</P>
<P>
<B>LESSONS FROM COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT</B></P>
<P>
Community development, which grew out of the civil rights movement, began as an
attempt  to build political empowerment, largely through community organizing. 
Many of these  initiatives made great progress in the short term but were not
self-perpetuating.  They did  not deal effectively with economic needs, even
though the plight of the target communities  was often caused by economic
factors.</P>
<P>
Several organizations (most notably South Shore Bank in Chicago, the Community 
Preservation Corporation in New York, the Enterprise Foundation in Baltimore,
and Local  Initiatives Support Corporation in New York) decided instead to focus
on economic  empowerment through community reinvestment.  They created
permanent, self-sustaining  development institutions to foster community renewal
through entrepreneurship.   Development banking, in particular, combined
for-profit business with a social mission,  using business tools and market
opportunities to release the energies of local residents and  effect change.</P>
<P>
This focus on entrepreneurs as agents of social change can be transferred to
conservation.   Community development combines human capital (creativity and
labor) and financial  capital to address social problems.  Conservation, in
turn, can help community  development become truly self-sustaining by including
natural capital - environmental  goods and services such as forests, clean air,
and clean water - in long-term reinvestment  strategies.</P>
<P>
Community development banking also offers useful lessons on attracting external
resources  to a community.  The most successful community development
institutions have been able  to attract resources not just from government, but
also from the private sector - individuals,  corporations, and foundations that
value a social as well as a financial return on their  dollar.  Increasingly,
investors are also seeking an environmental &quot;return&quot; from their 
investments, just as environmentally conscious consumers are affecting the
marketplace by  weighing social and environmental benefits when choosing goods
and services.</P>
<P>
The convergence of community development, conservation, and socially and 
environmentally responsible investors and consumers has led to a new approach to
 sustainability:  conservation-based development.  Guided by the ethics of
environmental  stewardship, economic equity, and social justice, while relying
on market incentives to  capture entrepreneurial energy and innovation,
conservation-based development presents a  radical agenda in a conservative
guise.</P>
<P>
<B>RESTORING MARKET AND NATURAL FORCES</B></P>
<P>
Creating the conditions for conservation-based development is no small task. 
There are  formidable barriers to its acceptance, including lack of
understanding, fear of change, an  infrastructure based on large-scale
production and cheap fossil fuels, and a plethora of  interests vested in the
status quo.  Only a powerful force can overcome these barriers.   Fortunately,
such a force exists:  the creative energy of  local residents who, given the
right  tools and incentives, have the commitment and capacity to be agents for
conservation- based development and social change.  Local residents, grounded in
a community through  family and historical ties, can develop that community's
resources for the best and most  restorative use.  Often, though, an outside
catalyst and resource broker is needed to help  restore the market and natural
forces for effective community-based conservation and  development.</P>
<P>
The challenge, then, is to create the conditions under which local residents,
working in  their own self-interest, will also contribute to ecosystem health
and community vitality.  If  this can be accomplished, then both market forces
and entrepreneurs' creativity and  innovation will have been harnessed for the
benefit of the ecosystem and the  community.</P>
<P>
What are the conditions that will cause this natural gravitation to
conservation-based  development?  They include access to information and
resources, local organizational  capacity, enhancement of entrepreneurial
capacity, and a policy environment that supports  appropriate development.  What
follows explores these conditions and provides examples  of initiatives to
establish this needed infrastructure.</P>
<P>
Ultimately, everything we need to live, from clean air to manufactured goods,
depends on a  healthy and productive ecosystem.  In urban settings, the
relationship between the goods  consumed and the ecosystem that produces them
may seem tenuous.  The ecological  footprint of urban area often extends around
the globe (see article by William Rees); if a  resource is exhausted in one
place, urban consumers can quickly move their purchasing  elsewhere.  In rural
communities dependent on natural resources, the relationship is more  direct;
deterioration of the natural environment has immediate and direct consequences.</P>
<P>
<B>Local Access to Relevant and Timely Information</B></P>
<P>
Developing long-term strategies for stewarding resources depends on accurate
information  regarding the distribution and condition of those resources and
their patterns of use.  A  growing number of initiatives in the Northwest focus
on brokering resource information to  local communities, facilitating local
stewardship.  Equally valuable are information  systems that describe social and
economic trends and document communities' progress  toward appropriate
conservation and development.  Developing such community indicators  of
sustainability is increasingly important.  Communities are identifying
indicators that  gauge residents' quality of life, sense of place, and optimism.
 Unlike traditional indicators,  which have measured &quot;progress&quot; by the
flow of market goods, community indicators weigh  ecological, social, and
economic factors, both tangible and intangible, that describe and  predict the
community's natural, human, and financial capital.  Indicators of Sustainability
 at the end of this article lists indicators devised by residents of Thurston
County,  Washington, to assess their progress toward their vision of a
sustainable society.</P>
<P>
<B>Secure Access to Resources</B></P>
<P>
For resource management to be sustainable, both the people who own resources and
those  who extract them must receive the full benefits of their investments and
stewardship.  In  addition, there must be some certainty about regulations and
tax structures.  Much of the  recent cutting of forests on private land -
especially mature forests that provide valuable  wildlife habitat - has been
prompted by fear of additional regulation to protect the spotted  owl, marbled
murrelet, and other threatened or endangered species.  In some cases, such 
responses have been self-serving, but in others, they reflect legitimate
concerns.  For many  rural residents, their land is both a source of income and
a legacy to their children, and  regulatory changes have significant
consequences.  We sometimes criticize the apparent  short-term perspective of
businesses, yet we reinforce it by providing an unpredictable  regulatory and
political environment.  At the same time, a more predictable regulatory  climate
and the ability to reap the benefits of stewardship must be balanced by the 
recognition that land and resource ownership brings responsibilities as well as
rights.</P>
<P>
<B>Local Organizational Capacity</B></P>
<P>
Many rural and inner-city communities developed as &quot;company towns,&quot; in
which  companies not only provided key economic activity, but also developed and
controlled key  infrastructure and civic activities.  Rural communities often
formed around mining, forest  products, or textile industries; inner-city
neighborhoods formed around steel mills,  slaughterhouses, and manufacturing. 
Depletion of raw materials or pursuit of cheaper  labor has caused the companies
to abandon the communities, often causing collapse of the  social infrastructure
as well.  Lack of organizational capacity has left communities both ill-
equipped to capture external resources and vulnerable to undesirable
development, such as  &quot;dirty&quot; industries and organized crime.</P>
<P>
A basic tenet of conservation-based development is that it can succeed only if
it captures  the vested interests and releases the creative energy of local
residents.  We cannot identify  and impose solutions to local environmental
problems from the outside, nor can solutions  come without local knowledge.  The
key, then, is to create permanent, locally controlled,  self-sustaining
organizations that can undertake conservation-based development by  articulating
a shared vision, coordinating initiatives, and brokering outside resources.  
Innovative, practical solutions are more likely when the issues are centered in
a specific  place and the decision-makers share a common commitment and context;
they are less  likely when the issues are abstract and the debate is
ideological.</P>
<P>
<B>Enhancement of Entrepreneurial Capacity</B></P>
<P>
Conservation-based entrepreneurs must understand and address the environmental
and  community implications of their business activities while, at the same
time, facing all the  usual challenges of doing business.  Business challenges
are greater in rural communities  and inner-city neighborhoods, where the
infrastructure is often underdeveloped or  deteriorated, markets are remote or
inaccessible, and resources and technical expertise are  limited.  With their
limited options, local communities continue to participate, often  unwillingly,
in the continued reduction of their natural capital by outside owners - and the 
export of the resulting benefits out of the region.</P>
<P>
<B>Supportive Policy Environment</B></P>
<P>
Conservation-based development depends on finding ways to provide stewardship 
incentives to entrepreneurs and communities.  As our economic, social, and
political  structures have become increasingly complex, governments' capacity to
address local  economic and environmental problems has diminished.  Much of the
support for community  renewal and ecosystem restoration must come from the
private sector and from market  forces.  A more favorable policy climate,
though, can expedite and enhance the reach of  private resources.</P>
<P>
The current tax and regulatory system provides powerful incentives for
unsustainable  business practices and formidable barriers to sustainability. 
The tax structure, for  example, discourages many timberland owners from
harvesting trees on longer rotations,  and fossil-fuel subsidies contribute to
the competitive advantage of imported over locally  grown foods.  Successful
conservation-based development requires that policymakers  follow the lead of
entrepreneurs and communities who identify these barriers through  practical
experience and suggest ways in which to restructure the tax and regulatory 
system.</P>
<P>
<B>THE POWER OF EXAMPLE</B></P>
<P>
Conservation-based development works on the power of example.  When a community 
reaches a critical mass of businesses exploring new ways to operate in a more
socially and  environmentally responsible manner, opportunities arise for
innovation on a larger scale.   A woodlot and mill owner, for example, might
work with the state to design a plan for  protecting an endangered species as
part of the company's forest management practices; the  state might then adapt
the plan for other forest land owners.  A company that has developed  a new
emission control system for cars might prompt the Environmental Protection
Agency  to rethink the way it categorizes automobile emissions.</P>
<P>
A market-based approach to community and ecosystem renewal creates a favorable
climate  for policy change outside the usual policy arena.  Supporting small
businesses that create  new markets for socially and environmentally responsible
goods and services builds the  consumer base for these products, which in turn
creates demand for more goods produced  in a sustainable manner.  These small
businesses often end up setting industry standards  and leading other, sometimes
larger, companies to change their practices.  Ultimately, if the  market demand
grows enough, or the small businesses show that they can increase their 
profitability and provide a social or environmental return, they can foster
change in an  entire economic sector.</P>
<P>
We will achieve greater economic sustainability only when businesses that
produce less  waste and reduce energy and raw material use become more
competitive in the  marketplace, at the same time that the costs of
unsustainable business practices and  products are internalized through higher
prices.</P>
<P>
For decades the conservation and environmental movements, overwhelmed by the
breadth  of changes needed to improve water and air quality, protect forest and
farmland, and  conserve endangered species, were forced into a defensive
posture.  Saying &quot;no&quot; to new  development, or considering the fate of
wild areas apart from the needs of adjacent  communities, seemed the only
strategy.  The effectiveness of these strategies has been  exhausted.</P>
<P>
Conservation-based development offers another strategy to complement these
earlier  approaches.  Drawing on the lessons of conservation and community
development, it  combines ecosystem restoration and community reinvestment.  A
growing alliance between  communities interested in ecosystem health and
socially responsible investors and  consumers can move us toward an economy in
which people's needs are met equitably and  within the earth's productive
capacity.</P>
<P>
<B><I>SHORETRUST:  MAKING CONSERVATION-BASED  DEVELOPMENT POSSIBLE</I></B></P>
<P>
<I>Ecotrust, a Portland-based conservation organization, recently joined forces
 with Chicago-based Shorebank Corporation, the nation's oldest community 
development banking institution.  Their goal:  to foster conservation-based 
development in the coastal temperate rain forest of the Pacific Northwest, 
focusing initially on Washington State's Willapa Bay watershed.</I></P>
<P>
While their partnership might seem unlikely, the two organizations agree on 
many basic principles:  the importance of mission, creating mechanisms to 
capture local innovation, restoring market and natural forces, targeting
specific  communities and ecosystems, and using comprehensive, system-based 
approaches.</P>
<P>
<B><I></I></B>The short-term goal of their partnership is to help individual 
businesses develop sound ways to manage their land and extract resources and  to
capture local value for communities.  The long-term goal is, to borrow from 
business entrepreneur Paul Hawken's <B>Ecology of Commerce</B>, &quot;to create
 a remarkably different economy, one that can restore ecosystems and protect the
 environment, while, bringing forth innovation, prosperity, meaningful work, and
 true security.&quot; <B></B></P>
<P>
<I>The vehicle for this conservation-based development strategy is a permanent 
development institution, a bank holding company called ShoreTrust, the First 
Environmental Bancorporation.  The holding company will own or control a  series
of entities offering financing, technical assistance, marketing, and  brokering
services for entrepreneurs and businesses providing environmental  benefits.</I></P>
<P>
Lending and marketing assistance at ShoreTrust are guided by conservation- based
development principles, which encourage businesses to utilize and reduce  waste,
save energy, add value locally, and enhance both human and biological 
productivity and diversity.  Client businesses are expected to show how they
will  modify their business activities to become more environmentally and
socially  restorative, and these plans become part of ShoreTrust's
loan-monitoring  guidelines.</P>
<P>
ShoreTrust is particularly interested in businesses that rely on a healthy, 
productive, and intact ecosystem for successful production.  Oyster growers, for
 example, have been active guardians of water quality in Willapa Bay, because 
oysters are extremely sensitive to deteriorating water quality.  Harvesters of 
wild edible mushrooms are another example; the mushrooms grow in intact 
forests, so both recreational and commercial harvests provide economic 
incentive for maintaining diverse, mature forests.  Helping businesses in these 
sectors strengthens the constituency for a healthy and intact ecosystem.</P>
<P>
A second group of important businesses makes use of waste products or 
underutilized resources.  These businesses provide tremendous opportunities 
because they not only produce revenues, they also reduce financial and 
ecological disposal costs.  One company, for example, uses wastes from fish-
processing plants to produce a variety of products, including organic
fertilizers  and fish meal.  The fertilizer is sold to cranberry growers to
replace imported  chemical fertilizers, keeping money in the community as well
as reducing  chemical runoff into the bay.</P>
<P>
<B><I>INDICATORS OF SUSTAINABILITY</I></B></P>
<P>
<I>In creating a vision for a sustainable community, residents of Thurston 
County, Washington, came up with the following indicators to gauge the quality 
of life in their community.  These indicators include ecological, social, and 
economic factors.</I></P>
<P>
In a sustainable community:</P>
<P>
  Resource consumption is balanced by resource assimilation by the  ecosystem. 
The sustainability of a community is largely determined by  the web of resources
providing its food, fiber, water, and energy needs  and by the ability of
natural systems to process its wastes (indicators include per capita water and
energy consumption from nonrenewable  sources, waste generation, and sales of
locally produced food).</P>
<P>
  A healthy natural environment sustains an abundant variety of human,  animal,
and plant life (indicators include the annual bird count and  returning salmon).</P>
<P>
  A diverse economy supports everyone through satisfying, productive work 
(indicators include the number and percent of people working for the five 
largest employers).</P>
<P>
  The basic needs of all are met, within a social environment that fosters 
active participation in political and cultural life, equity, cooperation,  and
respect for all (indicators include the number and percent of people  living
below the poverty level).</P>
<P>
  Everyone is engaged in lifelong education.  Throughout their lives,  people
develop the skills, knowledge, and attitudes needed to participate  actively in
a complex, interdependent, rapidly changing society  (indicators include the
high school graduation rate).</P>
<P>
  People are generally in good health physically, emotionally, and  spiritually
(indicators include the number and percent of babies born  with low birth
weight).</P>
<P>
  Most daily needs can be met by foot, bicycle, or public transportation.  
Public and private vehicles are powered by clean, renewable fuels  (indicators
include percent of commuters driving along).</P>
<P>
  Population size is within the &quot;carrying capacity&quot; of the land,
water, and  air (indicators include the total population).</P>
<P>
Excerpted from the 1993 &quot;State of the Community:  A Sustainable  Community
Roundtable Report on Progress Toward a Sustainable Society  in the South Puget
Sound Region.&quot; </P>
<P>
<B><I>WOODNET</I></B></P>
<P>
<I>WoodNet, a flexible manufacturing network of wood products businesses in 
Washington State, addresses three conditions for conservation-based 
development:  creation of local organizational capacity, secure access to 
resources, and enhancement of entrepreneurial capacity.</I></P>
<P>
WoodNet's creation in 1991 was prompted by a local effort to help the Olympic 
Peninsula's small and medium-sized wood products manufacturers, who were 
struggling with the economic challenges arising from decreased timber harvests. 
 The Olympic Peninsula's economic base was focused on the export and primary 
processing of logs, commodity-based businesses that stimulated high competition 
and little collaboration.  Given the decline in resource availability, WoodNet 
was created to nurture a shift from commodity product manufacture to the 
marketing and manufacture of value-added secondary wood products, such as 
cabinets, furniture, musical instruments, and boats.  This new strategy required
 collaboration and networking as well as a fundamental shift toward 
understanding the consumer, identifying niche markets, and focusing on quality 
and efficient small-scale production.</P>
<P>
WoodNet is a member-driven organization that represents firms ranging in size 
from one to fifty employees.  WoodNet's tools include group training, special 
group projects, and confidential one-on-one management and technical 
assistance.  WoodNet has produced full-color catalogs featuring members' 
product lines and has organized delegations to domestic and foreign trade 
shows.  It has also facilitated both meetings with bankers and access to raw 
materials by acting as a clearinghouse for using byproducts of members' 
manufacturing processes.  In addition, WoodNet regularly conducts training 
sessions on product pricing, promotion, distribution, market research, loan 
packaging, and financial management.</P>
<P>
Working through WoodNet, manufacturers are now able to pool resources,  overcome
common threats, and capitalize on previously unavailable market  opportunities.
&quot;Working together, member firms now engage in business none  could do
alone,&quot; says Gus Kostopulos, WoodNet's executive director.  As a  result,
the network is now an often-cited model for industries undergoing major 
restructuring.  Through collaboration, smaller manufacturers enjoy economies  of
scale and scope in production, purchasing, and marketing.  Thus, they gain  the
competitive strength generally enjoyed only by large manufacturers, without 
incurring the tremendous capital investment and resulting lack of flexibility
and  innovation typical of larger firms.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
  
<!--**foot**--></P>
<P>
 
</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></P>
<P>
Excerpted from &quot;WoodNet:  A Flexible Manufacturing Strategy&quot; by Todd
Thomas  in The Environment and People of the Coastal Temperate Rain Forest,
Peter  Schoonmaker, Bettina von Hagen, and Edward Wolf, in press.</P>
