<HEAD>
<TITLE>WHAT IF...WE MEASURED PROSPERITY IN NEW WAYS?</TITLE>
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="suscomm.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A> 
<A HREF="/articles/">
<IMG
ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/bugs/articles.gif" ALT="= Publications, Manuals, and Software ="></A>
<BR CLEAR="all"><BR> 
</P>
<H1><B>WHAT IF...</B></H1>
<H1><B>...WE MEASURED PROSPERITY IN NEW WAYS?</B></H1>
<H2><B>Wingspread Journal, Volume 18, Issue 2 Spring 1996</B></H2>     
<P>
<IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif">
<!--**head**-->
</P>
<P></P>   
<P>Ask an economist how America is doing and chances are you will get a bunch
of numbers: gross domestic product (GDP), the Dow Jones Industrial average,
import/export ratios.  These numbers can be useful indicators of the financial
health of the United States, but they don't begin to tell the real story about
the economic, social, and cultural health of the country.  They can't describe
whether or not our communities are thriving and what needs to change to make
them better.</P>
<P>Last year the World Bank released a study proposing that nations replace
their GDP figures with a new &quot;sustainable wealth of nations measure&quot;
that includes the value of natural resources, environmental protection,
education, and health&#151;in addition to the more traditional measurements of
machinery and infrastructure.  According to <I>Developing Ideas,</I> a
publication of the International Institute for Sustainable Development in
Winnipeg, Manitoba, this new measure would put the Australian and Canadian
economics first, with the United States lagging in 12th place.</P>
<P>William Rees, who directs the School of Community and Regional Planning at
the University of British Columbia, suggests another way to measure a
community's impact: determine its &quot;ecological footprint.&quot;  Writing in
<I>Northwest Report,</I> Rees proposes estimating the area of productive land
required to produce the material and energy needed for, and to absorb the waste
produced by, specific patterns of material consumption.  Under this formula, the
average American uses about 10 to 12 acres of productive land to support
consumer lifestyle.</P>
<P>Europeans are no better.  By some estimates, the ecological footprint of the
city of London is estimated to be about 125 times its real surface area,
equivalent to the entire productive land of Britain.  If our Western consumer
lifestyle were adopted by the entire world population of 10 billion, 125 billion
acres of productive land would be needed to support humankind.  Unfortunately,
the earth has only 22 billion acres of such land available.  Clearly, by the
measurement of our ecological footprints, our consumption and resource use need
serious examination.</P>
<P>A growing number of communities around the world has decided to do just
that: re-examine the impact of their communities on the environment.  In the
process, cities and towns are learning how to re-define acceptable growth.</P>
<P>Sustainable Seattle, a civic forum founded in 1990 and involving more than
250 volunteers, has developed 40 &quot;Indicators of Sustainable Community,&quot;
with the express goal of encouraging Seattle residents to help create a more
sustainable community.  The indicators include some things you would expect&#151;such
as the amount of solid waste recycled and the amount of open urban space&#151;and
some you might not&#151;such as availability of arts instruction and number of
youth involved in service.  The indicators were selected based on contributions
from citizens and are Seattle's response to the challenge of creating a future
for the next generation.</P>
<P>Sustainable Seattle suggests that such indicators can be used to help inform
the shaping of public policy, to create an agenda for issues covered by the
media, to help businesses plan for sustainable development, to educate students
and serve as models for new programs, to help non-profits and volunteers set
priorities, and to challenge individuals to explore how to make a difference. 
In choosing indicators, however, Sustainable Seattle recommends that each
indicator fulfill five criteria:</P>
<P>&#149; Indicators reflect something basic and fundamental to the long-term
cultural, economic, environmental, or social health of a community over
generations.
<BR></P>
<P>&#149; Indicators are accepted by the community and are understood to be
valid signs of sustainability or distress.
<BR></P>
<P>&#149; Indicators are attractive to the media and can be used to monitor,
analyze, and communicate local trends.
<BR></P>
<P>&#149; Indicators are statistically measurable.  If data is not readily
available, a practical method of data collection or measurement can be created.
<BR></P>
<P>&#149; Indicators are logically or scientifically defensible and general
conclusions can be drawn from them.</P>
<P>Is it possible for us to reshape our communities in more sustainable and
healthy ways? As Kathy Fletcher of People for Puget Sound says, &quot;Start now,
define some criteria, and in each and every decision, pick that option that
trends toward sustainability.  That way we will gradually get on a sustainable
course.&quot;</P>
<P><I>Sustainable Seattle's</I></P>
<P><B>40 Indicators for Sustainable Community</B></P>
<P><B>Environment</B><B><SUP>__________________________________________________________</SUP></B></P>
<P>&#144;  Wild Salmon  &#144;  Pedestrian-friendly streets</P>
<P>&#144;  Wetlands  &#144;  Open space in urban villages</P>
<P>&#144;  Biodiversity  &#144;  Impervious surfaces</P>
<P>&#144;  Soil erosion    (paved spaces)</P>
