<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Center of Excellence: The Green House</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P><A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
</P><CENTER><H2>THE GREEN HOUSE</H2><H3>Colorado Homebuilders Learn Buyers Support <BR>
Environmentally Sensitive Construction Methods<BR>
by Steve Raabe</H3><H3>The Denver Post
2/11/96</H3></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P>

<P>Call it the greening of the homebuilding industry.

<P>Colorado’s builders are jumping on the environmental bandwagon.  No longer content to leave environmentalism to the Birkenstock crowd, homebuilders hope to find out if "green" homes contribute to green bank accounts.

<P>Early signs suggest that green construction-the use of recycled, non-toxic and energy-saving materials-is the proverbial win-win solution for builders and homebuyers.

<P>Builders believe that green homes provide a powerful marketing tool for attracting buyers in metro Denver’s contracting new-home market.  Buyers are discovering that the marginally higher costs of green construction are more than offset by lower utility bills and special financing incentives - not to mention the psychic satisfaction of sensitivity to the environment.

<P>"It used to be that buyers would yawn when environmental and energy issues came up," said David Johnston, president of Boulder-based environmental construction firm What’s Working.  "We’d ask if they want more insulation; they’d say they would rather have nicer cabinets."

<P>But environmental awareness has increased exponentially in recent years, he said.  "Now we’re seeing a consumer response in the marketplace that anything we do to promote green issues is being embraced," Johnston said.  "When people become aware of the choices that are available, they ask why every home isn’t built this way."

<P>Public acceptance of the issue has made Colorado one of the nation’s leaders in the green building movement.

<P>A unique collaboration between the state government, a public utility and a homebuilders trade group is being watched closely as a pilot program that could become a national model for environmental homebuilding.

<P>"I see it as a builder’s responsibility to become accountable for some of the problems in energy waste and toxic materials," said Brian Roznowski, president of Ashland Custom Homes Inc. in Boulder.  "My homes cost a little more, but my buyers know they’re getting a lot more in energy efficiency and a safer home in the interior environment."

<P>The birth of the Colorado’s green movement began in 1987 when Public Service Co. of Colorado initiated its Ideal Energy Home program.  Simply a marketing plan to promote homebuilders that voluntarily build energy-efficient homes, the program has grown gradually to a current level of 180 participating builders.

<P>But recently, the green building movement has found new partners and an aggressive new approach.

<P>The Home Builders Association of Metro Denver and the Colorado Housing and Finance Authority have joined forces with PSC, with financial support provided by the Colorado Office of Energy Conservation.

<P>The partners have begun marketing their programs jointly and have made their different measurements of energy-efficiency uniform.

<P>Here’s how their programs work:
<UL>
<LI>The Green Builder Program is a brand-new effort sponsored by the Home Builders Association of Metro Denver.  It’s a marketing plan in which builders voluntarily agree to use recycled, energy-efficient and non-toxic building materials.
</UL>

<P>Builders must choose 35 building techniques or materials from a list of more than 100 options supplied by the HBA.  No certification or testing of homes is required; compliance is self-monitored by the builders.
<UL>
<LI>Energy Rated Homes of Colorado is an energy-rating program operated by the Colorado Housing and Finance Authority.  Homes are tested by certified raters, and the home’s energy efficiency is translated into a scale of points or stars up to a maximum of 100 points or five stars.
</UL>

<P>Buyers of homes rated as energy efficient may qualify for an "Energy Efficient Mortgage," in which income guidelines are relaxed so that a buyer can obtain a larger mortgage with less income.  The rationale is that homeowners can  make larger mortgage payments because they’ll be spending less on utility bills.  

<P>For example, a new home with a four-star energy rating would enable buyers with a household income of $50,000 to pay $12,150 more than the $143,865 price they’d typically qualify for on a 30-year, 7.25 percent FHA mortgage, based on a conventional 29 percent debt-to-income ratio.

<P>In addition, the program includes "Energy Improvement Mortgages" that allow buyers to incorporate the costs of planned energy-saving improvements into the mortgage loan.
<UL>
<LI>Public Service Co.’s Ideal Energy Home program is undergoing a transformation.  Formerly a voluntary and self-monitored marketing program for builders, IEH is creating a new classification called E-Star Builder that requires homes to be tested for energy ratings.
</UL>

<P>The ratings will correspond with Energy Rated Homes of Colorado criteria for energy efficiency.  As a result, builders in IEH will get a marketing boost by showing evidence of efficiency, and buyers will be eligible for the mortgage "stretch" provided by Energy Rated Homes.

<P>PSC will continue to offer a less-stringent program that calls for builders to use 10 prescriptive measures for energy saving.  As before, it will rely on self-compliance.

<P>With either program, builders will be required to construct all of their homes to IEH standards in order to call themselves IEH builders.

<P>Bill Smart, Public Service Co., program manager for Ideal Energy Homes, acknowledged that some homebuilders - including a few large, production builders - have used the IEH label on their homes without complying with prescriptive guidelines.

<P>He said the new policy of certification for E-Star homes will be a much more effective marketing tool for builders because homebuyers will know they are getting the energy efficiency implied by IEH.

<P>However, he anticipates that the current enrollment of 180 builders in IEH will drop significantly as the energy certification requirement takes effect in April.

<P>"We all know that in the industry, it’s just not true when every builder says all of their homes are energy efficient," Smart said.  "With the new program, builders who are really complying with the program will get the recognition they deserve."

<P>When the Home Builders Association began planning the Green Builder program last year, there was lengthy debate on whether homes should be tested, or left to self-monitoring by builders.

<P>The association opted for self-monitoring.  "But even if the builders are not 100 percent there (in compliance) on the first few homes," said Johnston of What’s Working, "at least they’re thinking about it.  That’s where we have to start." 

    

<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P>
