<HEAD><TITLE>Project XL for Communities</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A> 
<A HREF="/pubs/">
<IMG
ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/bugs/pubs.gif" ALT="= Publications, Manuals, and Software ="></A>
<BR CLEAR="all"><BR> 
</P>
<H1><B>Project XL for Communities</B></H1>
<H1><B>Environmental e<I>X</I>cellence and 
<I>L</I>eadership</B></H1>
<H2><B>Environmental Protection Agency, March 1996</B></H2>
<P><B><I>Creative, common sense strategies for superior environmental
protection</I></B></P>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif">
<!--**head**-->
</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>XL FOR COMMUNITIES (XLC) PILOT PROGRAM:</B></P>
<P>
Regulatory Flexibility for Environmental Results</P>
<P>
Project XLC promotes regulatory flexibility for communities in exchange for
greater  environmental benefits.  These benefits must be superior to those
achieved through full  compliance with current and anticipated regulations.  EPA
prefers strategies that will build  cooperation among citizens, businesses,
non-profit organizations and governments at the  community level.  To ensure
that the project objectives and requirements are achieved,  monitoring,
reporting and evaluation methods must be identified.</P>
<P>
<B>Stakeholder Support &#151; A Strong XLC Component</B></P>
<P>
EPA will not move forward with projects unless State or Tribal Regulatory
Agencies are  full partners.  Applicants are encouraged to consult with and seek
support of those agencies  while developing proposals.  In addition, because a
community's environment affects all of  its residents, community involvement and
support is one of the XLC selection criteria.</P>
<P>
<B>WHAT IS PROJECT XL?</B></P>
<P>
Alternative Path to Superior Environmental Results</P>
<P>
Project XL is a flagship program to reinvent environmental regulations.  XL is
an  opportunity for communities, facilities, industry sector, and government
agencies to  demonstrate environmental eXcellence and Leadership (XL).  EPA
provides a flexible and  innovative approach to regulatory requirements in
exchange for a commitment to greater  environmental results .</P>
<P>
The November 1, 1995 <I>Federal Register </I>notice (60 <I>FR 55569</I>)
continues to  solicit XL proposals from communities.  Over the next two years,
EPA plans to select 50  XL projects.</P>
<P>
<B>Quick Review and Selection Process</B></P>
<P>
Project XLC is a new way for EPA to conduct business.  EPA requests that
applicants  submit concise proposals to aid EPA in efficiently and effectively
reviewing them.  EPA's  Regional and Program Offices and State or Tribal
Agencies review the proposals within  approximately eight weeks.  EPA then
selects proposals and begins to negotiate with the  applicant to develop the
Final Project Agreement.  Final Project Agreements are expected  to be completed
within six months.</P>
<P>
<B>XL for Facilities, Industry Sectors, and Government Agencies</B></P>
<P>
In addition to XL for Communities, Project XL also includes XL for Facilities,
Industry  Sectors, and Government Agencies&#151;initiatives to give regulated
private sector sources  and government agencies the flexibility to develop
alternative strategies that replace or  modify specific regulatory requirements
on the condition that they produce greater  environmental benefits.  In exchange
for greater flexibility, regulated entities are held to a  higher standard of
accountability for demonstrating project results.  The program  encourages
participants to incorporate project plans into their broader strategic plans.</P>
<P>
<B>How to Create an XLC Project</B></P>
<P>
Local governments, nonprofit organizations, neighborhood groups, business
associations,  and others interested in creating an XLC project must submit a
proposal (four copies) to  the following address:</P>
<P>
<B>Regulatory Reinvention</B></P>
<P>
Pilot Projects<BR>FRL 5322-9<BR> Water Docket, Mailcode 4101<BR>US EPA<BR>
401 M Street, SW<BR>Washington, DC 20460</P>
<P>
The proposals are accepted on a rolling basis with no set end date.  Applicants
are  encouraged to explain the relationship between the proposal and the
selection criteria,  except for the enforcement and compliance criterion.</P>
<P>
<B>Selection Criteria</B></P>
<UL><LI>Superior Environmental Results</LI>
<LI>Stakeholder Involvement, Support, and Capacity for Community Participation</LI>
<LI> Economic Opportunity</LI>
<LI> Feasibility</LI>
<LI>Transferability</LI>
<LI>Monitoring, Reporting, and Evaluation</LI>
<LI>Equitable Distribution of Environmental Risks</LI>
<LI>Community Planning</LI>
<LI>Innovation/Multi-Media Focus/Pollution Prevention</LI>
<LI>Enforcement and Compliance History</LI></UL>
<P>
<B>XLC Contacts</B></P>
<P>
For more information, please contact the XL for Communities information line,
the EPA  regional lead in your area, EPA Headquarters or the Project XLC
HomePage:</P>
<P>
<B>XL for Communities Information Line</B></P>
<P>
(703) 934-3241</P>
<P>
<B>Headquarters</B></P>
<P>
